en ID maps to a dense vector through vector embedding of model hidden size before attention runs."},"114":{"id":"/docs/glossary/token-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/token","type":"heading","tags":["attention","token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/token#heading-0","content":"Token"},"115":{"id":"/docs/glossary/token-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/token","type":"heading","tags":["attention","token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/token#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"116":{"id":"/docs/glossary/token-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/token","type":"heading","tags":["attention","token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/token#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"117":{"id":"/docs/glossary/token-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/token","type":"heading","tags":["attention","token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/token#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"118":{"id":"/docs/glossary/token-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/token","type":"heading","tags":["attention","token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/token#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"119":{"id":"/docs/glossary/token-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/token","type":"heading","tags":["attention","token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/token#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"120":{"id":"/docs/glossary/token-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/token","type":"heading","tags":["attention","token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/token#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"121":{"id":"/docs/glossary/token-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/token","type":"heading","tags":["attention","token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/token#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"122":{"id":"/docs/glossary/token-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/token","type":"heading","tags":["attention","token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/token#heading-8","content":"References"},"123":{"id":"/docs/glossary/token-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/token","tags":["attention","token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/token#Token","content":"The smallest unit of text a language model reads and predicts—usually a word piece, not always a whole word. Each token ID maps to a dense vector through vector embedding of model hidden size before attention runs.\n\nToken\nThe smallest unit of text a language model reads and predicts—usually a word piece, not always a whole word. Each token ID maps to a dense vector through vector embedding of model hidden size before attention runs.\nModels use a fixed tokenizer vocabulary—mapping text to integer IDs that are embedded and scored—to drive next-token prediction rather than reading raw characters directly.\nWhat It Is\nA token is one step in the model's discrete text vocabulary. Subword tokenizers often split rare words into pieces so the vocabulary stays finite while still covering open vocabulary text.\nWhy It Matters\nTokenization sets context length in tokens, shapes cost per request, and determines whether two strings look identical to the model. Mismatched tokenizers between training and serving are a common integration bug. When someone says \"128k context,\" they mean 128k tokens—the same units the tokenizer emits before embeddings and next-token scoring. Use the related docs below to step from tokens into embeddings and onward toward logits and softmax.\nSimple Example\nThe phrase \"language models\" might become two or three tokens depending on the tokenizer. Each ID is looked up in an embedding table before attention layers run.\nWhere It Appears\nTokens appear at the input embedding layer, in autoregressive next-token scoring, and in KV-cache accounting during decoding. Attention modules operate on token positions, not raw characters. From here, follow the curated link to embeddings to continue the token-to-probability chain.\nCommon Confusions\nTokens are not always words; byte-level BPE can emit single-character tokens. Token count also differs from word count and from Unicode grapheme count.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nDiagram showing text flowing through a tokenizer into token IDs and embeddings\nHow raw text becomes token IDs before the transformer stack"},"124":{"id":"/docs/glossary/token-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/token","tags":["attention","token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/token","content":"tokens"},"125":{"id":"/docs/glossary/token-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/token","tags":["attention","token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/token","content":"token id"},"126":{"id":"/docs/glossary/token-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/token","tags":["attention","token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/token","content":"subword token"},"127":{"id":"/docs/glossary/token-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/token","tags":["attention","token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/token","content":"token"},"128":{"id":"/docs/glossary/token-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/token","tags":["attention","token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/token","content":"attention"},"129":{"id":"/docs/glossary/token-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/token","tags":["attention","token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/token","content":"attention mechanism"},"130":{"id":"/docs/glossary/token-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/token","tags":["attention","token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/token","content":"token-to-probability-chain"},"131":{"id":"/docs/glossary/token-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/token","tags":["attention","token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/token","content":"t