oising-generation","type":"page","content":"Denoising Generation","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation"},"142":{"id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","content":"A generation paradigm that starts from noisy latents and iteratively removes noise—or adds structure—until a clean sample emerges."},"143":{"id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation#heading-0","content":"Denoising Generation"},"144":{"id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"145":{"id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"146":{"id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"147":{"id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"148":{"id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"149":{"id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"150":{"id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"151":{"id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation#heading-8","content":"References"},"152":{"id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation#Denoising Generation","content":"A generation paradigm that starts from noisy latents and iteratively removes noise—or adds structure—until a clean sample emerges.\n\nDenoising Generation\nA generation paradigm that starts from noisy latents and iteratively removes noise—or adds structure—until a clean sample emerges.\nDenoising generation maintains a continuous noised state and repeatedly applies a network trained to predict noise or score so the state moves toward a plausible sample.\nWhat It Is\nTraining corrupts data with a noise schedule; at inference the model walks backward along that schedule (or integrates a flow) from pure noise to structured output. U-Nets, DiT blocks, and score networks act as denoisers operating on latents or pixels. Unlike autoregressive generation, each step updates the full spatial or channel tensor rather than appending one discrete token.\nWhy It Matters\nDenoising generation is the second major output family beside autoregressive decoding and explains diffusion models, score-based samplers, and many image or audio generators. It ties directly to latent, latent space, and generative-model taxonomy pages and contrasts with token-chain decoding on decoders.\nSimple Example\nA text-to-image diffusion model starts from Gaussian noise in latent space, runs fifty denoising steps conditioned on a text embedding, and decodes the final latent through a VAE to pixels.\nWhere It Appears\nStable Diffusion-style latent diffusion, audio denoisers, video diffusion, and flow-matching samplers all iterate denoising updates. Conditioning pages describe how prompts, class labels, or guidance weights attach to each step in both denoising and autoregressive setups.\nCommon Confusions\nDenoising generation is not the same as a denoising autoencoder used only for representation learning—generation requires a sampling loop that produces new outputs. It is also not autoregressive token decoding even when implemented with transformer blocks; the state being updated is usually a full latent grid. A single forward pass that reconstructs clean data from noise without iteration is denoising, but not necessarily the full generative paradigm unless used inside a multi-step sampler.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nTrack the working tensor: noise in → repeated denoiser updates → clean latent or pixels out."},"153":{"id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","content":"Denoising generation"},"154":{"id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","content":"denoising decoder"},"155":{"id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","content":"iterative denoising"},"156":{"id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","content":"noise removal generation"},"157":{"id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","content":"foundations"},"158":{"id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","content":"foundational concepts"},"159":{"id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"160":{"id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","content":"core vocabulary"},"161":{"id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","content":"taxonomy"},"162":{"id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","content":"glossary taxonomy"},"163":{"id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","content":"atlas taxonomy"},"164":{"id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","content":"taxonomy glossary"},"165":{"id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation-23","page_id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","content":"cross-family taxonomy"},"166":{"id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation-24","page_id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","content":"foundations"},"167":{"id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation-25","page_id":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/denoising-generation","content":"taxonomy"},"168":{"id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","page_id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","type":"page","content":"Discriminative Model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model"},"169":{"id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","content":"A model trained to score, rank, or classify inputs into labels or preferences rather than synthesize new content."},"170":{"id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model#heading-0","content":"Discriminative Model"},"171":{"id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"172":{"id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"173":{"id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"174":{"id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"175":{"id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"176":{"id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"177":{"id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"178":{"id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model#heading-8","content":"References"},"179":{"id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model#Discriminative Model","content":"A model trained to score, rank, or classify inputs into labels or preferences rather than synthesize new content.\n\nDiscriminative Model\nA model trained to score, rank, or classify inputs into labels or preferences rather than synthesize new content.\nA discriminative model estimates p(label | input) or preference scores from inputs rather than learning a full generative distribution over outputs.\nWhat It Is\nDiscriminative models include classifiers, rerankers, and reward models used in RLHF. They consume representations from shared backbones and output decisions or scalar scores. The role is orthogonal to architecture: transformers are used in both generative and discriminative setups.\nWhy It Matters\nKnowing a checkpoint is discriminative sets expectations for metrics (accuracy, AUROC, calibration) and for how it pairs with generative models in pipelines.\nSimple Example\nA BERT-style encoder with a classification head for sentiment is discriminative. The same encoder body might later be fine-tuned into a generative decoder, but the discriminative training objective only predicts labels from text.\nWhere It Appears\nDiscriminative model appears in moderation stacks, retrieval reranking, and alignment literature next to generative model and foundation model entries.\nCommon Confusions\nDiscriminative versus generative describes training and inference goals, not whether the network is large or small. A reward model that scores completions is discriminative even when it sits beside a generative chat model. Discriminative is also not the same as \"non-foundation\": many foundation checkpoints are fine-tuned into discriminative heads.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nIf the output is a label, score, or ranking over existing options, use discriminative; if the system fabricates new tokens or media, use generative."},"180":{"id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","content":"discriminative models"},"181":{"id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","content":"classifier"},"182":{"id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","content":"discriminative classifier"},"183":{"id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","content":"taxonomy"},"184":{"id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","content":"glossary taxonomy"},"185":{"id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","content":"atlas taxonomy"},"186":{"id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","content":"taxonomy glossary"},"187":{"id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","content":"cross-family taxonomy"},"188":{"id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","content":"foundations"},"189":{"id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","content":"foundational concepts"},"190":{"id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"191":{"id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","content":"core vocabulary"},"192":{"id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model-23","page_id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","content":"taxonomy"},"193":{"id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model-24","page_id":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/discriminative-model","content":"foundations"},"194":{"id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm","page_id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm","type":"page","content":"Layer norm","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm"},"195":{"id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm","content":"Per-token mean-and-variance normalization that rescales each hidden vector before the next sublayer in a transformer block."},"196":{"id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm#heading-0","content":"Layer norm"},"197":{"id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"198":{"id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"199":{"id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"200":{"id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm#heading-4","content":"Formula And Symbols"},"201":{"id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"202":{"id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"203":{"id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"204":{"id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm#heading-8","content":"References"},"205":{"id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm#Layer norm","content":"Per-token mean-and-variance normalization that rescales each hidden vector before the next sublayer in a transformer block.\n\nLayer norm\nPer-token mean-and-variance normalization that rescales each hidden vector before the next sublayer in a transformer block.\nLayer norm recenters and rescales each token's hidden vector using mean and variance across its features, then applies learned scale and shift before the next sublayer runs.\nWhat It Is\nLayer normalization (LayerNorm) rescales one token's hidden vector by subtracting the mean across its features, dividing by a stabilized standard deviation, then applying learned scale and shift parameters. Statistics are computed per position, not across the batch or sequence, which matches how decoder transformers process variable-length text.\nWhy It Matters\nOriginal transformer stacks used layer norm around attention and feed-forward sublayers to keep activations stable as depth grows. Many encoder-decoder and early decoder models still rely on it. Understanding the mean-centering step helps when you compare layer norm with RMSNorm, which drops the mean subtraction but keeps per-feature scaling.\nSimple Example\nAfter self-attention, one token vector might have features ranging from -3 to 12. Layer norm measures the mean and spread across those features, divides by the stabilized scale, then multiplies by learned gain γ and adds learned bias β. The feed-forward network receives a vector whose feature magnitudes sit in a predictable band.\nFormula And Symbols\nThe rescale below applies to one token position. Each symbol names a quantity in that vector, not a batch-wide statistic.\nCommon Confusions\nLayer norm is not batch norm: it never pools statistics across examples in a minibatch. It is also not the residual add—that path preserves the skip stream while norm actively rescales it. RMSNorm is a close cousin that omits mean centering; both are layer-style norms used inside transformer blocks rather than across tokens.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences"},"206":{"id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm","content":"LayerNorm"},"207":{"id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm","content":"layer normalization"},"208":{"id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm","content":"LN"},"209":{"id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm","content":"foundations"},"210":{"id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm","content":"foundational concepts"},"211":{"id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"212":{"id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm","content":"core vocabulary"},"213":{"id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/layer-norm","content":"foundations"},"214":{"id":"/docs/glossary/gradient","page_id":"/docs/glossary/gradient","type":"page","content":"Gradient","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/gradient"},"215":{"id":"/docs/glossary/gradient-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/gradient","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/gradient","content":"The direction and size of change each parameter should take to reduce the training loss."},"216":{"id":"/docs/glossary/gradient-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/gradient","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/gradient#heading-0","content":"Gradient"},"217":{"id":"/docs/glossary/gradient-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/gradient","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/gradient#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"218":{"id":"/docs/glossary/gradient-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/gradient","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/gradient#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"219":{"id":"/docs/glossary/gradient-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/gradient","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/gradient#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"220":{"id":"/docs/glossary/gradient-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/gradient","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/gradient#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"221":{"id":"/docs/glossary/gradient-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/gradient","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/gradient#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"222":{"id":"/docs/glossary/gradient-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/gradient","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/gradient#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"223":{"id":"/docs/glossary/gradient-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/gradient","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/gradient#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"224":{"id":"/docs/glossary/gradient-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/gradient","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/gradient#heading-8","content":"References"},"225":{"id":"/docs/glossary/gradient-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/gradient","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/gradient#Gradient","content":"The direction and size of change each parameter should take to reduce the training loss.\n\nGradient\nThe direction and size of change each parameter should take to reduce the training loss.\nA gradient is the partial derivative of the loss with respect to a parameter or activation; optimizers step in the opposite direction to reduce loss.\nWhat It Is\nFor each trainable parameter, the gradient records how much the scalar loss would change if that parameter increased slightly. Frameworks store gradients in `.grad` tensors aligned with parameter shapes. Gradients flow backward from the loss through the computational graph, applying the chain rule at each differentiable op.\nWhy It Matters\nWithout gradients, you cannot run stochastic gradient descent, Adam, or other optimizers. Debugging training often starts by checking whether gradients are zero, exploding, or detached from the graph. The same logits-to-loss path that produced predictions also defines which parameters receive non-zero gradients.\nSimple Example\nImagine a single weight w in a tiny linear layer. If increasing w by a tiny amount raises the loss, the gradient ∂L/∂w is positive and an optimizer subtracts a small multiple of that value from w on the next step.\nWhere It Appears\nPyTorch and JAX populate parameter gradients after `loss.backward()` or `grad` transforms. Mixed-precision training may keep master weights in float32 while gradients accumulate in wider dtypes for stability. Distinctive chain phrase: reverse-mode loss gradient on every trainable parameter.\nCommon Confusions\nGradients are not the same as parameter values or activations—they are update hints computed from the current batch. A zero gradient on a parameter often means it did not affect the loss (frozen, disconnected, or saturated). Gradients also differ from momentum buffers or optimizer state, which accumulate across steps.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nGradient answers how much each parameter should change to reduce loss. Backpropagation is the algorithm that fills those gradients by walking the graph backward."},"226":{"id":"/docs/glossary/gradient-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/gradient","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/gradient","content":"gradients"},"227":{"id":"/docs/glossary/gradient-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/gradient","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/gradient","content":"partial derivative"},"228":{"id":"/docs/glossary/gradient-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/gradient","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/gradient","content":"loss gradient"},"229":{"id":"/docs/glossary/gradient-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/gradient","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/gradient","content":"token-to-probability-chain"},"230":{"id":"/docs/glossary/gradient-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/gradient","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/gradient","content":"token to probability chain"},"231":{"id":"/docs/glossary/gradient-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/gradient","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/gradient","content":"phase 2 probability chain"},"232":{"id":"/docs/glossary/gradient-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/gradient","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/gradient","content":"foundations probability path"},"233":{"id":"/docs/glossary/gradient-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/gradient","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/gradient","content":"foundations"},"234":{"id":"/docs/glossary/gradient-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/gradient","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/gradient","content":"foundational concepts"},"235":{"id":"/docs/glossary/gradient-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/gradient","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/gradient","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"236":{"id":"/docs/glossary/gradient-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/gradient","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/gradient","content":"core vocabulary"},"237":{"id":"/docs/glossary/gradient-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/gradient","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/gradient","content":"token-to-probability-chain"},"238":{"id":"/docs/glossary/gradient-23","page_id":"/docs/glossary/gradient","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/gradient","content":"foundations"},"239":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alibi","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alibi","type":"page","content":"ALiBi","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/alibi"},"240":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alibi-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alibi","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/alibi","content":"Attention with linear biases adds distance-based penalties to attention logits so models can extrapolate to longer sequences without explicit position embeddings."},"241":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alibi-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alibi","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/alibi#heading-0","content":"ALiBi"},"242":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alibi-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alibi","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/alibi#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"243":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alibi-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alibi","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/alibi#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"244":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alibi-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alibi","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/alibi#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"245":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alibi-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alibi","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/alibi#heading-4","content":"Common Confusions"},"246":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alibi-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alibi","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/alibi#heading-5","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"247":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alibi-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alibi","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/alibi#heading-6","content":"Tags"},"248":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alibi-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alibi","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/alibi#heading-7","content":"References"},"249":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alibi-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alibi","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/alibi#ALiBi","content":"Attention with linear biases adds distance-based penalties to attention logits so models can extrapolate to longer sequences without explicit position embeddings.\n\nALiBi\nAttention with linear biases adds distance-based penalties to attention logits so models can extrapolate to longer sequences without explicit position embeddings.\nALiBi adds distance-based linear biases to attention logits so relative position shapes scores without explicit position embeddings, which helps some models extrapolate beyond their training length.\nWhat It Is\nAttention with linear biases (ALiBi) encodes token order by subtracting a slope-scaled penalty from each attention logit based on how far apart the query and key positions are. Nearby pairs keep stronger scores and distant pairs are pushed down, so the model learns relative distance without storing a separate position vector per index. ALiBi is applied directly on attention logits after the usual query-key dot products, not by rotating vectors or adding absolute position tables to embeddings.\nWhy It Matters\nALiBi was introduced to help transformers trained on shorter sequences generalize when inference spans grow longer, because the bias pattern can extend smoothly beyond the training length. Teams sometimes choose ALiBi when they want length extrapolation without maintaining rotary angle tables or learned absolute embeddings. It also keeps the embedding layer free of position-specific parameters, which can simplify certain training setups compared with sinusoidal or learned absolute schemes.\nSimple Example\nImagine attention comparing a query at position ten to keys at positions eight, nine, and eleven. ALiBi subtracts a small bias for the two-step gap to position eight, a smaller bias for the one-step gap to position nine, and again a small bias for the one-step gap to position eleven. The raw content match still matters, but distance steadily damps far-away keys. Each attention head can use its own slope, so some heads emphasize local context while others tolerate wider spans.\nCommon Confusions\nALiBi is not RoPE: RoPE rotates query and key vectors so their dot product encodes relative distance, while ALiBi leaves those vectors unchanged and adds explicit distance penalties to logits afterward. ALiBi is also not the same as a causal mask, which only blocks future tokens rather than grading how far apart allowed pairs are. Finally, ALiBi does not remove context-window limits by itself—memory and attention cost still grow with sequence length even when biases extrapolate cleanly.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences"},"250":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alibi-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alibi","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/alibi","content":"ALiBi"},"251":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alibi-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alibi","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/alibi","content":"attention with linear biases"},"252":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alibi-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alibi","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/alibi","content":"attention linear bias"},"253":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alibi-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alibi","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/alibi","content":"foundations"},"254":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alibi-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alibi","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/alibi","content":"foundational concepts"},"255":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alibi-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alibi","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/alibi","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"256":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alibi-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alibi","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/alibi","content":"core vocabulary"},"257":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alibi-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alibi","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/alibi","content":"foundations"},"258":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","type":"page","content":"Generative Model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/generative-model"},"259":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","content":"A model trained to produce new outputs such as text, images, or audio rather than only assign labels to fixed categories."},"260":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/generative-model#heading-0","content":"Generative Model"},"261":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/generative-model#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"262":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/generative-model#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"263":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/generative-model#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"264":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/generative-model#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"265":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/generative-model#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"266":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/generative-model#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"267":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/generative-model#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"268":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/generative-model#heading-8","content":"References"},"269":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generative-model#Generative Model","content":"A model trained to produce new outputs such as text, images, or audio rather than only assign labels to fixed categories.\n\nGenerative Model\nA model trained to produce new outputs such as text, images, or audio rather than only assign labels to fixed categories.\nA generative model learns a distribution over outputs and samples or decodes new examples—tokens, pixels, or waveforms—conditioned on inputs or prompts.\nWhat It Is\nGenerative models optimize objectives that support sampling or decoding: next-token prediction, denoising score matching, or latent diffusion. They may start from a foundation model base but the generative role describes what the trained artifact does at inference, not its parameter count alone.\nWhy It Matters\nSeparating generative from discriminative models clarifies evaluation (likelihood, sample quality) and which atlas families—diffusion, autoregressive language models—apply to a product.\nSimple Example\nAn autoregressive language model that completes prompts token by token is generative. A spam filter that outputs spam versus not-spam without synthesizing new mail is discriminative, even if both use transformers.\nWhere It Appears\nGenerative model shows up in product categories, safety benchmarks for synthetic media, and links to representation when discussing latent spaces used for sampling.\nCommon Confusions\nGenerative versus discriminative is about the training objective and inference behavior, not model size. A generative model is not the same as a foundation model: many foundation checkpoints are adapted into discriminative classifiers. Generative models also differ from representation learning alone—representations can support both roles depending on the head.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nIf the system creates new content you could not pick from a fixed label list, treat it as generative; if it only chooses among known classes, look at the discriminative model page."},"270":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","content":"generative models"},"271":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","content":"generator"},"272":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","content":"generative AI"},"273":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","content":"taxonomy"},"274":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","content":"glossary taxonomy"},"275":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","content":"atlas taxonomy"},"276":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","content":"taxonomy glossary"},"277":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","content":"cross-family taxonomy"},"278":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","content":"foundations"},"279":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","content":"foundational concepts"},"280":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"281":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","content":"core vocabulary"},"282":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model-23","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","content":"taxonomy"},"283":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model-24","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generative-model","content":"foundations"},"284":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generalization","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generalization","type":"page","content":"Generalization","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/generalization"},"285":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generalization-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generalization","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generalization","content":"How well a model performs on data it was not explicitly trained to memorize—validation sets, new domains, and live traffic are the practical tests."},"286":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generalization-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generalization","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/generalization#heading-0","content":"Generalization"},"287":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generalization-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generalization","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/generalization#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"288":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generalization-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generalization","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/generalization#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"289":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generalization-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generalization","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/generalization#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"290":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generalization-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generalization","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/generalization#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"291":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generalization-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generalization","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/generalization#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"292":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generalization-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generalization","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/generalization#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"293":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generalization-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generalization","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/generalization#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"294":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generalization-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generalization","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/generalization#heading-8","content":"References"},"295":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generalization-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generalization","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generalization#Generalization","content":"How well a model performs on data it was not explicitly trained to memorize—validation sets, new domains, and live traffic are the practical tests.\n\nGeneralization\nHow well a model performs on data it was not explicitly trained to memorize—validation sets, new domains, and live traffic are the practical tests.\nGeneralization is useful performance on held-out or shifted data—the ability to apply stable structure learned in training when inputs change modestly or domains differ.\nWhat It Is\nGeneralization measures whether learned patterns transfer beyond the exact training examples—via validation splits, out-of-domain tests, or online A/B metrics. It depends on capacity, data diversity, optimization, and regularization; alignment and filtering change behavior but do not replace statistical generalization.\nWhy It Matters\nCustomers care about reliability on new prompts, users, and modalities, not training-set accuracy. Naming generalization separately from overfitting and capacity clarifies why bigger models can generalize better yet still fail on adversarial or out-of-scope inputs.\nSimple Example\nA language model trained on English helpdesk logs answers Spanish product questions reasonably well because it learned task structure, not ticket IDs—until domain shift is so large that even good generalization breaks down.\nWhere It Appears\nHeld-out validation during pretraining, robustness benchmarks, and monitoring live error rates after deployment. Overfitting and model capacity pages describe the training-side levers; evaluation metrics such as perplexity quantify probabilistic generalization for language models.\nCommon Confusions\nGeneralization is not guaranteed by scale alone—data and objectives matter. It is also not the same as instruction-following quality, which mixes capability with alignment. Perfect training accuracy with poor test accuracy indicates failed generalization, often via overfitting.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nAsk what distribution the score was measured on and whether the model saw those examples during training."},"296":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generalization-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generalization","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generalization","content":"Generalization"},"297":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generalization-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generalization","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generalization","content":"generalize"},"298":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generalization-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generalization","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generalization","content":"held-out performance"},"299":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generalization-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generalization","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generalization","content":"test set generalization"},"300":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generalization-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generalization","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generalization","content":"foundations"},"301":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generalization-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generalization","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generalization","content":"foundational concepts"},"302":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generalization-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generalization","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generalization","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"303":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generalization-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generalization","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generalization","content":"core vocabulary"},"304":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generalization-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generalization","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generalization","content":"taxonomy"},"305":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generalization-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generalization","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generalization","content":"glossary taxonomy"},"306":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generalization-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generalization","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generalization","content":"atlas taxonomy"},"307":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generalization-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generalization","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generalization","content":"taxonomy glossary"},"308":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generalization-23","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generalization","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generalization","content":"cross-family taxonomy"},"309":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generalization-24","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generalization","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generalization","content":"foundations"},"310":{"id":"/docs/glossary/generalization-25","page_id":"/docs/glossary/generalization","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/generalization","content":"taxonomy"},"311":{"id":"/docs/glossary/world-model","page_id":"/docs/glossary/world-model","type":"page","content":"World Model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"url":"/docs/glossary/world-model"},"312":{"id":"/docs/glossary/world-model-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/world-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/world-model","content":"A model family that learns environment dynamics or state transitions so it can predict or simulate what happens next."},"313":{"id":"/docs/glossary/world-model-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/world-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"url":"/docs/glossary/world-model#heading-0","content":"World Model"},"314":{"id":"/docs/glossary/world-model-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/world-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"url":"/docs/glossary/world-model#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"315":{"id":"/docs/glossary/world-model-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/world-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"url":"/docs/glossary/world-model#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"316":{"id":"/docs/glossary/world-model-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/world-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"url":"/docs/glossary/world-model#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"317":{"id":"/docs/glossary/world-model-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/world-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"url":"/docs/glossary/world-model#heading-4","content":"Common Confusions"},"318":{"id":"/docs/glossary/world-model-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/world-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"url":"/docs/glossary/world-model#heading-5","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"319":{"id":"/docs/glossary/world-model-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/world-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"url":"/docs/glossary/world-model#heading-6","content":"Tags"},"320":{"id":"/docs/glossary/world-model-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/world-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"url":"/docs/glossary/world-model#heading-7","content":"References"},"321":{"id":"/docs/glossary/world-model-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/world-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/world-model#World Model","content":"A model family that learns environment dynamics or state transitions so it can predict or simulate what happens next.\n\nWorld Model\nA model family that learns environment dynamics or state transitions so it can predict or simulate what happens next.\nWorld models learn how states change over time—predicting the next observation, latent state, or reward from the current situation—so agents can plan, simulate, or roll out imagined trajectories before acting.\nWhat It Is\nA world model learns how an environment evolves: given the current state and an action or input, it predicts the next state, observation, or reward. Implementations range from compact latent dynamics models in model-based reinforcement learning to large video predictors that roll forward imagined frames. The family name covers any network trained primarily to model transitions rather than to answer open-ended text prompts.\nWhy It Matters\nWorld models sit beside language-only transformers and image generators as a distinct architecture family because success depends on whether weights capture actionable dynamics, not just static patterns. Knowing the family separates simulation stacks used for planning from chat models that describe environments in words. The architecture page groups world models with other families; this page is the dedicated reference for learned environment dynamics and state transitions.\nSimple Example\nA robot policy trainer encodes camera frames and proprioception into a latent state, trains a recurrent or transformer dynamics head to predict the next latent state given the current state and motor command, then uses those rollouts to evaluate candidate actions before executing them on hardware.\nCommon Confusions\nWorld model names a family focused on transition prediction, not any product marketed as understanding the world. Representation names the internal vectors after encoding; generative model names the broader class that can synthesize outputs; conditioning names controls that steer generation. A language model that narrates physics in text is not automatically a world model unless its weights are trained to predict environment state transitions.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences"},"322":{"id":"/docs/glossary/world-model-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/world-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/world-model","content":"world models"},"323":{"id":"/docs/glossary/world-model-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/world-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/world-model","content":"world modeling"},"324":{"id":"/docs/glossary/world-model-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/world-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/world-model","content":"environment model"},"325":{"id":"/docs/glossary/world-model-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/world-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/world-model","content":"taxonomy"},"326":{"id":"/docs/glossary/world-model-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/world-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/world-model","content":"glossary taxonomy"},"327":{"id":"/docs/glossary/world-model-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/world-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/world-model","content":"atlas taxonomy"},"328":{"id":"/docs/glossary/world-model-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/world-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/world-model","content":"taxonomy glossary"},"329":{"id":"/docs/glossary/world-model-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/world-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/world-model","content":"cross-family taxonomy"},"330":{"id":"/docs/glossary/world-model-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/world-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/world-model","content":"model-family"},"331":{"id":"/docs/glossary/world-model-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/world-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/world-model","content":"model families"},"332":{"id":"/docs/glossary/world-model-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/world-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/world-model","content":"architecture families"},"333":{"id":"/docs/glossary/world-model-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/world-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/world-model","content":"model family"},"334":{"id":"/docs/glossary/world-model-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/world-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/world-model","content":"taxonomy"},"335":{"id":"/docs/glossary/world-model-23","page_id":"/docs/glossary/world-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/world-model","content":"model-family"},"336":{"id":"/docs/glossary/normalization","page_id":"/docs/glossary/normalization","type":"page","content":"Normalization","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/normalization"},"337":{"id":"/docs/glossary/normalization-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/normalization","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/normalization","content":"Layers that rescale hidden vectors inside each transformer block so activations stay stable as depth and batch composition change."},"338":{"id":"/docs/glossary/normalization-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/normalization","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/normalization#heading-0","content":"Normalization"},"339":{"id":"/docs/glossary/normalization-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/normalization","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/normalization#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"340":{"id":"/docs/glossary/normalization-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/normalization","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/normalization#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"341":{"id":"/docs/glossary/normalization-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/normalization","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/normalization#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"342":{"id":"/docs/glossary/normalization-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/normalization","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/normalization#heading-4","content":"Common Confusions"},"343":{"id":"/docs/glossary/normalization-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/normalization","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/normalization#heading-5","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"344":{"id":"/docs/glossary/normalization-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/normalization","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/normalization#heading-6","content":"Tags"},"345":{"id":"/docs/glossary/normalization-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/normalization","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/normalization#heading-7","content":"References"},"346":{"id":"/docs/glossary/normalization-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/normalization","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/normalization#Normalization","content":"Layers that rescale hidden vectors inside each transformer block so activations stay stable as depth and batch composition change.\n\nNormalization\nLayers that rescale hidden vectors inside each transformer block so activations stay stable as depth and batch composition change.\nNormalization layers keep each token's hidden vector on a stable scale inside transformer blocks, most often with per-position layer norm or RMSNorm instead of batch norm.\nWhat It Is\nNormalization layers rescale each hidden vector so its numeric spread stays in a predictable range before the next sublayer runs. In transformers, that usually means applying a layer-style norm across the features inside one token vector—computing statistics per position rather than across the whole minibatch. A learned scale and shift then let the model recover useful signal after the rescale.\nWhy It Matters\nDeep stacks multiply many matrix operations; without normalization, activations can drift or explode and training becomes fragile. Transformers favor layer norm or RMSNorm because sequence length and batch size change at inference time, while batch norm depends on batch-wide statistics that are unstable for variable-length text. Recognizing the normalization slot in each block helps you read whether a model uses pre-norm or post-norm placement around attention and the feed-forward network.\nSimple Example\nPicture one token vector leaving self-attention with uneven feature magnitudes. A layer norm step measures spread across that vector's dimensions, divides by a stabilized scale, and applies learned gain and bias. The feed-forward network then sees a well-scaled input. The same recipe repeats after the FFN before the residual add hands the vector to the next block.\nCommon Confusions\nNormalization is not the residual add: residuals preserve a skip path, while norm layers actively rescale activations. Layer norm and RMSNorm are the common transformer choices; batch norm is rare in decoder stacks because per-batch mean and variance are a poor fit for variable sequence batches. Finally, normalization does not mix tokens—each position is normalized on its own feature vector.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences"},"347":{"id":"/docs/glossary/normalization-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/normalization","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/normalization","content":"normalization layer"},"348":{"id":"/docs/glossary/normalization-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/normalization","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/normalization","content":"norm layer"},"349":{"id":"/docs/glossary/normalization-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/normalization","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/normalization","content":"foundations"},"350":{"id":"/docs/glossary/normalization-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/normalization","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/normalization","content":"foundational concepts"},"351":{"id":"/docs/glossary/normalization-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/normalization","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/normalization","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"352":{"id":"/docs/glossary/normalization-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/normalization","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/normalization","content":"core vocabulary"},"353":{"id":"/docs/glossary/normalization-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/normalization","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/normalization","content":"foundations"},"354":{"id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting","page_id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting","type":"page","content":"Overfitting","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/overfitting"},"355":{"id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/overfitting","content":"When a model fits training noise so closely that held-out or production data perform worse—the classic gap between memorization and useful generalization."},"356":{"id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/overfitting#heading-0","content":"Overfitting"},"357":{"id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/overfitting#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"358":{"id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/overfitting#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"359":{"id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/overfitting#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"360":{"id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/overfitting#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"361":{"id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/overfitting#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"362":{"id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/overfitting#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"363":{"id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/overfitting#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"364":{"id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/overfitting#heading-8","content":"References"},"365":{"id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/overfitting#Overfitting","content":"When a model fits training noise so closely that held-out or production data perform worse—the classic gap between memorization and useful generalization.\n\nOverfitting\nWhen a model fits training noise so closely that held-out or production data perform worse—the classic gap between memorization and useful generalization.\nOverfitting means the model memorized spurious training patterns that fail on validation or live data, often visible when validation loss rises while training loss keeps falling.\nWhat It Is\nOverfitting is poor generalization caused by excessive fit to the training distribution: the model minimizes training loss by memorizing examples instead of learning stable features. High capacity, noisy labels, and too many training steps relative to data size are common drivers.\nWhy It Matters\nOverfitting is the mirror of generalization: product quality depends on held-out performance, not training curves alone. Linking overfitting to model capacity, loss design, and alignment data hygiene keeps architecture, training, and evaluation vocabulary consistent.\nSimple Example\nA classifier reaches 99% training accuracy but 60% on a validation set because it memorized background textures in training photos. Adding augmentation, early stopping, or weight decay widens the train–validation gap in the right direction.\nWhere It Appears\nFine-tuning small datasets on large language models, tabular models with leaky features, and diffusion models that reproduce training captions verbatim. Loss-function and optimizer-state concepts describe the training machinery that must be regularized to reduce overfitting.\nCommon Confusions\nOverfitting is not the same as underfitting or pure distribution shift: shift can hurt test performance even without memorization. Low training loss alone is not proof of overfitting—you need a comparison set. Memorizing public benchmarks is a form of overfitting to evaluation, not just training rows.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nCompare training and validation curves—divergence with great training metrics is the overfitting smell test."},"366":{"id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/overfitting","content":"Overfitting"},"367":{"id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/overfitting","content":"overfit"},"368":{"id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/overfitting","content":"memorization"},"369":{"id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/overfitting","content":"training set memorization"},"370":{"id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/overfitting","content":"foundations"},"371":{"id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/overfitting"