"type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/embedding#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"516":{"id":"/docs/glossary/embedding-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/embedding","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/embedding#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"517":{"id":"/docs/glossary/embedding-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/embedding","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/embedding#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"518":{"id":"/docs/glossary/embedding-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/embedding","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/embedding#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"519":{"id":"/docs/glossary/embedding-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/embedding","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/embedding#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"520":{"id":"/docs/glossary/embedding-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/embedding","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/embedding#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"521":{"id":"/docs/glossary/embedding-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/embedding","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/embedding#heading-8","content":"References"},"522":{"id":"/docs/glossary/embedding-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/embedding","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/embedding#Embedding","content":"A dense vector that represents a token or other discrete item so the model can run continuous math on it.\n\nEmbedding\nA dense vector that represents a token or other discrete item so the model can run continuous math on it.\nAn embedding table maps each discrete token ID to a learned vector so the model can mix information in continuous space before deeper layers run.\nWhat It Is\nAn embedding is a fixed-size list of numbers (a vector) associated with a discrete symbol such as a token ID. In transformer language models, the input embedding layer converts each position's token ID into a vector of model width (hidden size).\nWhy It Matters\nEmbeddings are where text becomes geometry: similar tokens can end up with nearby vectors after training, and every later layer operates on those vectors. Context length, batching, and memory all count embedding rows when you size a deployment.\nSimple Example\nSuppose token ID 42 maps to a 768-dimensional vector. A sequence of three tokens becomes a 3×768 tensor of embeddings before the first attention block runs.\nWhere It Appears\nEmbeddings sit at the bottom of decoder-only transformers, in encoder inputs for seq2seq models, and in retrieval systems that compare query and document vectors. Positional information is usually added to embeddings before attention.\nCommon Confusions\nAn embedding is not the same as a one-hot vector: the table stores dense learned weights rather than a single 1 in a huge sparse vector. Embeddings are also not logits or probabilities—they are inputs, not outputs of the vocabulary head.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nFollow the chain forward: after embeddings become tensors, the model eventually produces logits and softmax probabilities for the next token."},"523":{"id":"/docs/glossary/embedding-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/embedding","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/embedding","content":"embeddings"},"524":{"id":"/docs/glossary/embedding-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/embedding","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/embedding","content":"token embedding"},"525":{"id":"/docs/glossary/embedding-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/embedding","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/embedding","content":"vector embedding"},"526":{"id":"/docs/glossary/embedding-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/embedding","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/embedding","content":"token-to-probability-chain"},"527":{"id":"/docs/glossary/embedding-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/embedding","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/embedding","content":"token to probability chain"},"528":{"id":"/docs/glossary/embedding-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/embedding","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/embedding","content":"phase 2 probability chain"},"529":{"id":"/docs/glossary/embedding-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/embedding","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/embedding","content":"foundations probability path"},"530":{"id":"/docs/glossary/embedding-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/embedding","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/embedding","content":"foundations"},"531":{"id":"/docs/glossary/embedding-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/embedding","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/embedding","content":"foundational concepts"},"532":{"id":"/docs/glossary/embedding-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/embedding","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/embedding","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"533":{"id":"/docs/glossary/embedding-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/embedding","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/embedding","content":"core vocabulary"},"534":{"id":"/docs/glossary/embedding-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/embedding","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/embedding","content":"token-to-probability-chain"},"535":{"id":"/docs/glossary/embedding-23","page_id":"/docs/glossary/embedding","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/embedding","content":"foundations"},"536":{"id":"/docs/glossary/activation","page_id":"/docs/glossary/activation","type":"page","content":"Activation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/activation"},"537":{"id":"/docs/glossary/activation-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/activation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/activation","content":"The numeric output of a layer after its linear transform and nonlinearity, passed forward through the network."},"538":{"id":"/docs/glossary/activation-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/activation","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/activation#heading-0","content":"Activation"},"539":{"id":"/docs/glossary/activation-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/activation","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/activation#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"540":{"id":"/docs/glossary/activation-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/activation","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/activation#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"541":{"id":"/docs/glossary/activation-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/activation","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/activation#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"542":{"id":"/docs/glossary/activation-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/activation","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/activation#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"543":{"id":"/docs/glossary/activation-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/activation","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/activation#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"544":{"id":"/docs/glossary/activation-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/activation","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/activation#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"545":{"id":"/docs/glossary/activation-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/activation","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/activation#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"546":{"id":"/docs/glossary/activation-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/activation","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/activation#heading-8","content":"References"},"547":{"id":"/docs/glossary/activation-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/activation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/activation#Activation","content":"The numeric output of a layer after its linear transform and nonlinearity, passed forward through the network.\n\nActivation\nThe numeric output of a layer after its linear transform and nonlinearity, passed forward through the network.\nAn activation is the tensor a layer outputs for a given input—hidden states in transformers are intermediate signals flowing between blocks until the vocabulary head produces logits, distinct from final softmax probabilities.\nWhat It Is\nAfter a layer applies its weights to an input tensor, the result (often after GELU, ReLU, or another nonlinearity) is that layer’s activation. In a transformer block, the post-attention and post-MLP tensors are typical activation examples.\nWhy It Matters\nActivations determine what information reaches the next layer and what backpropagation will differentiate. Memory planners track activation tensors during training because they are large but temporary, unlike checkpointed parameters.\nSimple Example\nFor a batch of one sequence, a hidden layer might output a tensor of shape (sequence_length, hidden_size). That tensor is the activation handed to the next sublayer.\nWhere It Appears\nProfiling tools chart activation magnitudes per layer. Interpretability work sometimes inspects specific activation directions. In inference, activations are usually recomputed on each forward pass rather than saved in the weight file.\nCommon Confusions\nA hidden activation is not the same as softmax: softmax turns vocabulary logits into a probability vector at the output head, while activations are internal layer outputs that may never be normalized across the vocabulary. Saying a “ReLU activation” refers to the nonlinearity applied inside a layer, not to the softmax step at decode time.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nParameters are the stored weights; activations are the live values those weights produce for your prompt as it moves through the stack."},"548":{"id":"/docs/glossary/activation-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/activation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/activation","content":"activations"},"549":{"id":"/docs/glossary/activation-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/activation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/activation","content":"hidden activation"},"550":{"id":"/docs/glossary/activation-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/activation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/activation","content":"layer output"},"551":{"id":"/docs/glossary/activation-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/activation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/activation","content":"token-to-probability-chain"},"552":{"id":"/docs/glossary/activation-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/activation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/activation","content":"token to probability chain"},"553":{"id":"/docs/glossary/activation-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/activation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/activation","content":"phase 2 probability chain"},"554":{"id":"/docs/glossary/activation-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/activation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/activation","content":"foundations probability path"},"555":{"id":"/docs/glossary/activation-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/activation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/activation","content":"foundations"},"556":{"id":"/docs/glossary/activation-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/activation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/activation","content":"foundational concepts"},"557":{"id":"/docs/glossary/activation-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/activation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/activation","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"558":{"id":"/docs/glossary/activation-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/activation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/activation","content":"core vocabulary"},"559":{"id":"/docs/glossary/activation-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/activation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/activation","content":"token-to-probability-chain"},"560":{"id":"/docs/glossary/activation-23","page_id":"/docs/glossary/activation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/activation","content":"foundations"},"561":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rope","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rope","type":"page","content":"RoPE","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/rope"},"562":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rope-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rope","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/rope","content":"Rotary position embedding rotates query and key vectors by token index so attention scores depend on relative distance, as used in Llama-class decoder models."},"563":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rope-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rope","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/rope#heading-0","content":"RoPE"},"564":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rope-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rope","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/rope#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"565":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rope-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rope","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/rope#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"566":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rope-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rope","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/rope#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"567":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rope-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rope","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/rope#heading-4","content":"Common Confusions"},"568":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rope-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rope","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/rope#heading-5","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"569":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rope-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rope","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/rope#heading-6","content":"Tags"},"570":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rope-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rope","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/rope#heading-7","content":"References"},"571":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rope-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rope","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/rope#RoPE","content":"Rotary position embedding rotates query and key vectors by token index so attention scores depend on relative distance, as used in Llama-class decoder models.\n\nRoPE\nRotary position embedding rotates query and key vectors by token index so attention scores depend on relative distance, as used in Llama-class decoder models.\nRoPE rotates query and key vectors by token position so attention scores reflect relative distance along the sequence, which is why many Llama-class decoders adopt it instead of absolute position tables.\nWhat It Is\nRotary position embedding (RoPE) encodes where a token sits in the sequence by rotating its query and key vectors in paired feature dimensions. Earlier positions use smaller rotation angles and later positions use larger ones, so the dot product between a query at one index and a key at another depends on their separation along the sequence. RoPE is applied inside the attention sublayer rather than as a separate additive position table on embeddings.\nWhy It Matters\nMany modern decoder language models—including Llama, Mistral, and Qwen families—use RoPE because it gives attention a built-in sense of relative distance without storing a fixed absolute position vector per index. That relative behavior also shapes how models behave when sequences grow longer than they saw during training: extrapolation and context-extension techniques often start from how RoPE angles are scaled or interpolated at new positions.\nSimple Example\nImagine two tokens five positions apart. RoPE rotates each token's query and key vectors by an amount tied to its index. When attention scores the pair, the rotation difference encodes a five-step gap, so the model can treat nearby tokens differently from far-away ones even though the raw hidden features alone carry no order. The same mechanism applies at every layer that uses standard multi-head attention with RoPE-enabled projections.\nCommon Confusions\nRoPE is not an attention variant like grouped-query or multi-query attention—it only changes how position enters the query and key spaces before the usual attention math runs. It is also not the same as ALiBi, which adds distance-based bias terms to attention logits instead of rotating vectors. Finally, RoPE does not by itself guarantee unlimited context: a model may still degrade on very long spans when rotation angles extrapolate beyond training.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences"},"572":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rope-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rope","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/rope","content":"RoPE"},"573":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rope-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rope","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/rope","content":"rotary position embedding"},"574":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rope-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rope","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/rope","content":"rotary positional embedding"},"575":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rope-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rope","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/rope","content":"foundations"},"576":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rope-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rope","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/rope","content":"foundational concepts"},"577":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rope-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rope","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/rope","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"578":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rope-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rope","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/rope","content":"core vocabulary"},"579":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rope-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rope","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/rope","content":"foundations"},"580":{"id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","page_id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","type":"page","content":"Hidden Size","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size"},"581":{"id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","content":"The width of a model's internal vectors—the number of dimensions in each token embedding and each token's per-position hidden state before the vocabulary projection."},"582":{"id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size#heading-0","content":"Hidden Size"},"583":{"id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"584":{"id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"585":{"id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"586":{"id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size#heading-4","content":"Common Confusions"},"587":{"id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size#heading-5","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"588":{"id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size#heading-6","content":"Tags"},"589":{"id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size#heading-7","content":"References"},"590":{"id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size#Hidden Size","content":"The width of a model's internal vectors—the number of dimensions in each token embedding and each token's per-position hidden state before the vocabulary projection.\n\nHidden Size\nThe width of a model's internal vectors—the number of dimensions in each token embedding and each token's per-position hidden state before the vocabulary projection.\nHidden size is the width of internal vectors in a transformer—every embedding and per-position hidden state uses that many dimensions until the output head.\nWhat It Is\nHidden size (also called model width or hidden dimension) is the length of the vectors flowing through a transformer's residual stream. Every token position carries a vector of that width after embedding lookup and through each block until the language-model head.\nWhy It Matters\nShape notation such as batch×sequence×768 uses hidden size as the last axis for activations inside the stack. Parameter counts, memory use, and FLOPs scale with width, so papers and configs often list hidden size alongside layer count and head count when comparing model sizes. For MLP expansion ratios, head-dimension splits, and scaling trade-offs, see the model capacity glossary entry.\nSimple Example\nGPT-2 small uses hidden size 768: each token embedding is a 768-dimensional vector, attention projects queries and keys within that space, and the MLP expands and contracts around the same width unless a config explicitly sets a different intermediate size.\nCommon Confusions\nHidden size is not vocabulary size—the embedding table has vocab_size rows but each row has hidden_size columns. It is also not the same as parameter count: two models can share width but differ in depth, head layout, or MLP expansion ratio.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences"},"591":{"id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","content":"hidden size"},"592":{"id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","content":"model width"},"593":{"id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","content":"hidden dimension"},"594":{"id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","content":"token-to-probability-chain"},"595":{"id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","content":"token to probability chain"},"596":{"id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","content":"phase 2 probability chain"},"597":{"id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","content":"foundations probability path"},"598":{"id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","content":"foundations"},"599":{"id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","content":"foundational concepts"},"600":{"id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"601":{"id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","content":"core vocabulary"},"602":{"id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","content":"token-to-probability-chain"},"603":{"id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/hidden-size","content":"foundations"},"604":{"id":"/docs/glossary/decoder","page_id":"/docs/glossary/decoder","type":"page","content":"Decoder","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/decoder"},"605":{"id":"/docs/glossary/decoder-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/decoder","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/decoder","content":"A network stack that turns internal representations into outputs—tokens, pixels, or structured predictions—often one step at a time with attention to prior context."},"606":{"id":"/docs/glossary/decoder-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/decoder","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/decoder#heading-0","content":"Decoder"},"607":{"id":"/docs/glossary/decoder-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/decoder","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/decoder#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"608":{"id":"/docs/glossary/decoder-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/decoder","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/decoder#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"609":{"id":"/docs/glossary/decoder-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/decoder","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/decoder#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"610":{"id":"/docs/glossary/decoder-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/decoder","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/decoder#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"611":{"id":"/docs/glossary/decoder-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/decoder","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/decoder#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"612":{"id":"/docs/glossary/decoder-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/decoder","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/decoder#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"613":{"id":"/docs/glossary/decoder-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/decoder","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/decoder#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"614":{"id":"/docs/glossary/decoder-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/decoder","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/decoder#heading-8","content":"References"},"615":{"id":"/docs/glossary/decoder-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/decoder","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/decoder#Decoder","content":"A network stack that turns internal representations into outputs—tokens, pixels, or structured predictions—often one step at a time with attention to prior context.\n\nDecoder\nA network stack that turns internal representations into outputs—tokens, pixels, or structured predictions—often one step at a time with attention to prior context.\nA decoder reads representations from an encoder or earlier blocks and maps them to an output space, often autoregressively or iteratively until a full sample is formed.\nWhat It Is\nDecoders include causal transformer stacks for language modeling, transposed convolutions or U-Net upsampling paths in image models, and cross-attention layers that query encoder memory in seq2seq systems. They consume representations—they do not patchify raw inputs unless the architecture is decoder-only end to end.\nWhy It Matters\nNaming decoders separately from encoders shows where generation happens, how KV caches apply during inference, and why encoder–decoder pairs differ from decoder-only GPT-style models. It also sets up autoregressive generation as the paradigm most decoders follow in language settings.\nSimple Example\nA machine-translation decoder attends to encoder memory while emitting target tokens left to right. A VAE decoder maps a latent vector back to a 64×64 image. A GPT-style stack is decoder-only: the same blocks both represent context and predict the next token.\nWhere It Appears\nDecoders appear in T5 and original transformer translation models, latent diffusion decoders, and all causal language models that predict next tokens. Encoder and encoder–decoder pages explain how representations are supplied before decoding begins.\nCommon Confusions\nA decoder is not always autoregressive—some decoders reconstruct in one shot—but language-model decoders almost always are. A decoder is also not the softmax head alone: the head sits on top of the decoder stack. Denoising generation is a separate paradigm that may reuse decoder-like U-Nets without autoregressive token steps.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nFollow the arrow from hidden states to outputs—that generative or reconstructive stack is the decoder, even when the model is labeled decoder-only."},"616":{"id":"/docs/glossary/decoder-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/decoder","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/decoder","content":"Decoder"},"617":{"id":"/docs/glossary/decoder-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/decoder","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/decoder","content":"decoder block"},"618":{"id":"/docs/glossary/decoder-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/decoder","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/decoder","content":"decoder stack"},"619":{"id":"/docs/glossary/decoder-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/decoder","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/decoder","content":"decoding network"},"620":{"id":"/docs/glossary/decoder-15","page_id":"/docs/gloss