},"685":{"id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"686":{"id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"687":{"id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"688":{"id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"689":{"id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"690":{"id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"691":{"id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model#heading-8","content":"References"},"692":{"id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model#Foundation Model","content":"A large pretrained model intended as a shared starting point for many downstream tasks via fine-tuning or prompting.\n\nFoundation Model\nA large pretrained model intended as a shared starting point for many downstream tasks via fine-tuning or prompting.\nA foundation model is pretrained at scale on broad data so teams can adapt it through fine-tuning, prompting, or distillation instead of training from scratch per task.\nWhat It Is\nIn this reference, a foundation model is a general-purpose pretrained checkpoint: wide data, large capacity, and an explicit role as a base for downstream use. It is still a model in the taxonomy sense—weights you can load—not an architecture diagram alone.\nWhy It Matters\nLabeling a release as a foundation model signals adaptation paths: which generative or discriminative heads are common, and how it relates to the plain model glossary entry for artifacts versus roles.\nSimple Example\nA 70B language model trained on mixed web and code text, then instruction-tuned for chat, often has a foundation pretraining stage and a later alignment stage. The foundation stage checkpoint is the shared base many products build on.\nWhere It Appears\nFoundation model appears in scaling papers, open-weight hubs, and policy discussions. Generative and discriminative model pages describe how teams specialize this base.\nCommon Confusions\nA foundation model is not automatically generative: the same base can feed classifiers or generators depending on heads and training. It is also not the same as any large model—a narrow specialist can be huge but not intended as a reusable base.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nAsk whether the checkpoint is marketed and licensed for broad reuse; if yes, treat it as a foundation model before you classify generative versus discriminative behavior."},"693":{"id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","content":"foundation models"},"694":{"id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","content":"base model"},"695":{"id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","content":"pretrained model"},"696":{"id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","content":"taxonomy"},"697":{"id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","content":"glossary taxonomy"},"698":{"id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","content":"atlas taxonomy"},"699":{"id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","content":"taxonomy glossary"},"700":{"id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","content":"cross-family taxonomy"},"701":{"id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","content":"foundations"},"702":{"id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","content":"foundational concepts"},"703":{"id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"704":{"id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","content":"core vocabulary"},"705":{"id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model-23","page_id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","content":"taxonomy"},"706":{"id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model-24","page_id":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/foundation-model","content":"foundations"},"707":{"id":"/docs/glossary/component","page_id":"/docs/glossary/component","type":"page","content":"Component","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/component"},"708":{"id":"/docs/glossary/component-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/component","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/component","content":"A finer-grained part inside a module, such as an attention head or projection layer."},"709":{"id":"/docs/glossary/component-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/component","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/component#heading-0","content":"Component"},"710":{"id":"/docs/glossary/component-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/component","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/component#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"711":{"id":"/docs/glossary/component-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/component","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/component#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"712":{"id":"/docs/glossary/component-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/component","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/component#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"713":{"id":"/docs/glossary/component-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/component","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/component#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"714":{"id":"/docs/glossary/component-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/component","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/component#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"715":{"id":"/docs/glossary/component-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/component","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/component#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"716":{"id":"/docs/glossary/component-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/component","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/component#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"717":{"id":"/docs/glossary/component-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/component","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/component#heading-8","content":"References"},"718":{"id":"/docs/glossary/component-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/component","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/component#Component","content":"A finer-grained part inside a module, such as an attention head or projection layer.\n\nComponent\nA finer-grained part inside a module, such as an attention head or projection layer.\nA component is a sub-part of a module that performs one identifiable job in the forward pass, smaller than a full repeating block in the stack.\nWhat It Is\nComponents include query/key/value projections, individual attention heads, layer-normalization cells, and gating units inside a larger block. They are the smallest units this taxonomy names before dropping to raw tensor ops.\nWhy It Matters\nClear component language helps you read architecture diagrams, follow sharding plans, and understand which part of a module changes when papers propose a new projection or norm placement.\nSimple Example\nMulti-head attention is a module; each head is a component with its own Q/K/V projections and output merge. Grouped-query attention changes how those components share key/value state.\nWhere It Appears\nComponent labels appear in detailed module diagrams, efficient-attention write-ups, and hardware partitioning docs. Module pages in this atlas may reference components when explaining internals.\nCommon Confusions\nComponents are not standalone modules—you rarely swap only a norm and call it a new architecture. They are also not parameters: a component is a structural role, while weights are the learned values filling that role.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nZoom out one level to \"module\" when the block has its own page in `/docs/modules/`; zoom in to \"component\" when you are inside that block."},"719":{"id":"/docs/glossary/component-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/component","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/component","content":"model component"},"720":{"id":"/docs/glossary/component-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/component","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/component","content":"layer component"},"721":{"id":"/docs/glossary/component-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/component","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/component","content":"sub-module"},"722":{"id":"/docs/glossary/component-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/component","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/component","content":"taxonomy"},"723":{"id":"/docs/glossary/component-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/component","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/component","content":"glossary taxonomy"},"724":{"id":"/docs/glossary/component-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/component","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/component","content":"atlas taxonomy"},"725":{"id":"/docs/glossary/component-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/component","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/component","content":"taxonomy glossary"},"726":{"id":"/docs/glossary/component-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/component","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/component","content":"cross-family taxonomy"},"727":{"id":"/docs/glossary/component-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/component","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/component","content":"foundations"},"728":{"id":"/docs/glossary/component-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/component","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/component","content":"foundational concepts"},"729":{"id":"/docs/glossary/component-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/component","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/component","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"730":{"id":"/docs/glossary/component-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/component","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/component","content":"core vocabulary"},"731":{"id":"/docs/glossary/component-23","page_id":"/docs/glossary/component","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/component","content":"taxonomy"},"732":{"id":"/docs/glossary/component-24","page_id":"/docs/glossary/component","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/component","content":"foundations"},"733":{"id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","page_id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","type":"page","content":"Conditioning","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/conditioning"},"734":{"id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","content":"Extra inputs—text prompts, class labels, images, or guidance weights—that steer a generative model without retraining the full parameter stack each time."},"735":{"id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/conditioning#heading-0","content":"Conditioning"},"736":{"id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/conditioning#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"737":{"id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/conditioning#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"738":{"id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/conditioning#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"739":{"id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/conditioning#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"740":{"id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/conditioning#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"741":{"id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/conditioning#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"742":{"id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/conditioning#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"743":{"id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/conditioning#heading-8","content":"References"},"744":{"id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/conditioning#Conditioning","content":"Extra inputs—text prompts, class labels, images, or guidance weights—that steer a generative model without retraining the full parameter stack each time.\n\nConditioning\nExtra inputs—text prompts, class labels, images, or guidance weights—that steer a generative model without retraining the full parameter stack each time.\nConditioning injects side information—prompts, class labels, or cross-attention context—so each generation step depends on both the current state and the control signal.\nWhat It Is\nConditioning signals are encoded—via text encoders, learned embeddings, or pooled features—and fused into the generative network at attention layers, FiLM layers, or as prepended tokens. Classifier-free guidance mixes conditional and unconditional forward passes in denoising models. Autoregressive models condition on prior tokens plus optional system or tool context in the prefix.\nWhy It Matters\nConditioning is the bridge between the two major generation paradigms: both autoregressive and denoising loops accept control inputs, but they attach them at different points in the stack. Understanding conditioning clarifies prompt engineering, adapter tuning, and why the same text encoder can steer image diffusion and multimodal chat.\nSimple Example\nA diffusion model receives a CLIP text embedding alongside each denoising step so \"a red bicycle\" shifts the score toward bicycle-shaped latents. A chat model prepends a system message token sequence so the autoregressive decoder sees policy instructions before the user turn.\nWhere It Appears\nText-to-image diffusion uses cross-attention conditioning; instruction-tuned language models use prefix conditioning; class-conditional GANs and diffusion use label embeddings. Autoregressive generation and denoising generation pages describe the loops that consume these signals.\nCommon Confusions\nConditioning is not fine-tuning: weights stay fixed while runtime inputs change behavior. It is also not the same as a hard constraint or decoder constraint algorithm—conditioning is learned soft steering. Prompt tokens in autoregressive models are conditioning, but not every context window entry is an independent control channel; some are simply prior generated tokens.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nAsk what extra signal is fused into each generation step and where in the network that fusion happens."},"745":{"id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","content":"Conditioning"},"746":{"id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","content":"conditional generation"},"747":{"id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","content":"control signal"},"748":{"id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","content":"classifier-free guidance"},"749":{"id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","content":"foundations"},"750":{"id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","content":"foundational concepts"},"751":{"id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"752":{"id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","content":"core vocabulary"},"753":{"id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","content":"taxonomy"},"754":{"id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","content":"glossary taxonomy"},"755":{"id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","content":"atlas taxonomy"},"756":{"id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","content":"taxonomy glossary"},"757":{"id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning-23","page_id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","content":"cross-family taxonomy"},"758":{"id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning-24","page_id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","content":"foundations"},"759":{"id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning-25","page_id":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/conditioning","content":"taxonomy"},"760":{"id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","page_id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","type":"page","content":"Backpropagation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation"},"761":{"id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","content":"The backward pass that applies the chain rule on a computational graph to compute gradients for every differentiable parameter."},"762":{"id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation#heading-0","content":"Backpropagation"},"763":{"id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"764":{"id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"765":{"id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"766":{"id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"767":{"id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"768":{"id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"769":{"id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"770":{"id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation#heading-8","content":"References"},"771":{"id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation#Backpropagation","content":"The backward pass that applies the chain rule on a computational graph to compute gradients for every differentiable parameter.\n\nBackpropagation\nThe backward pass that applies the chain rule on a computational graph to compute gradients for every differentiable parameter.\nBackpropagation reuses the forward graph in reverse so each op propagates loss derivatives into its inputs until every parameter receives a gradient for the optimizer.\nWhat It Is\nBackpropagation (often shortened to backprop) is reverse-mode automatic differentiation specialized for neural networks. Starting at the loss node, the framework multiplies local Jacobians along edges of the computational graph so earlier parameters receive credit for how they influenced the final error.\nWhy It Matters\nIt makes deep networks trainable without hand-derived derivatives for every layer. The same code that computed logits, softmax, and cross-entropy loss can call backward once and populate gradients on embeddings, attention projections, and output weights consistently.\nSimple Example\nConsider logits → softmax → cross-entropy. Backpropagation first yields ∂L/∂logits, then continues through earlier matmuls and activations. Each step applies the chain rule so ∂L/∂W for a weight matrix W combines upstream loss sensitivity with the forward input that multiplied W.\nWhere It Appears\nEvery mainstream training stack exposes backprop via `.backward()`, `grad`, or `value_and_grad`. Checkpointing trades extra forward recomputation for memory by not storing every activation. Distinctive chain phrase: backward pass through the autograd graph after forward logits.\nCommon Confusions\nBackpropagation is not the optimizer step—it only computes gradients. It is also not forward inference: no weight updates happen during backward unless you explicitly call an optimizer. Reverse-mode autodiff is efficient for many parameters and one scalar loss, which is the usual language-model training setup.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nForward pass builds the graph; backpropagation walks it backward to fill `.grad`. The loss-function page completes the story from predictions to the scalar you differentiate."},"772":{"id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","content":"backprop"},"773":{"id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","content":"backward pass"},"774":{"id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","content":"reverse-mode autodiff"},"775":{"id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","content":"token-to-probability-chain"},"776":{"id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","content":"token to probability chain"},"777":{"id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","content":"phase 2 probability chain"},"778":{"id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","content":"foundations probability path"},"779":{"id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","content":"foundations"},"780":{"id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","content":"foundational concepts"},"781":{"id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"782":{"id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","content":"core vocabulary"},"783":{"id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","content":"token-to-probability-chain"},"784":{"id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation-23","page_id":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/backpropagation","content":"foundations"},"785":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","type":"page","content":"Model Capacity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity"},"786":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","content":"How much function a model can represent—driven by parameter count, width, depth, and training data—before optimization and regularization constrain what it actually learns."},"787":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity#heading-0","content":"Model Capacity"},"788":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"789":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"790":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"791":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"792":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"793":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"794":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"795":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity#heading-8","content":"References"},"796":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity#Model Capacity","content":"How much function a model can represent—driven by parameter count, width, depth, and training data—before optimization and regularization constrain what it actually learns.\n\nModel Capacity\nHow much function a model can represent—driven by parameter count, width, depth, and training data—before optimization and regularization constrain what it actually learns.\nModel capacity is the upper bound on patterns an architecture could fit given its parameters and depth, while data, loss design, and regularization determine how much of that bound training actually uses.\nWhat It Is\nModel capacity describes expressive power: wider layers, more heads, and more parameters increase the space of functions the network can represent. It is distinct from compute budget (how much training you can afford) and from measured generalization (how well the model works on new inputs).\nWhy It Matters\nCapacity sits between architecture choices and training outcomes. Too little capacity underfits; too much capacity without enough data or regularization invites overfitting. Scaling law and perplexity pages connect capacity trends to measurable evaluation signals.\nSimple Example\nA tiny two-layer network may memorize a thousand training points but fail on a held-out set, while a wider network with dropout and more diverse data achieves lower validation loss—the second model had enough capacity used well, not just more parameters for its own sake.\nWhere It Appears\nWidth and depth ablations, scaling studies that plot loss versus parameter count, and capacity planning for fine-tuning adapters versus full-weight updates. Parameter count links this page to the token-and-optimization chain even when a dedicated parameter glossary page is still planned.\nCommon Confusions\nCapacity is not the same as context length or inference speed. More parameters do not guarantee better generalization if optimization or data are mismatched. Adapter parameters add some capacity but do not replace the expressiveness of the frozen base weights they modulate.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nAsk how many independent degrees of freedom the model has and whether the training setup can fill them without memorizing noise."},"797":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","content":"Model capacity"},"798":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","content":"capacity"},"799":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","content":"expressive capacity"},"800":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","content":"model size"},"801":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","content":"foundations"},"802":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","content":"foundational concepts"},"803":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"804":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","content":"core vocabulary"},"805":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","content":"taxonomy"},"806":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","content":"glossary taxonomy"},"807":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","content":"atlas taxonomy"},"808":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","content":"taxonomy glossary"},"809":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity-23","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","content":"cross-family taxonomy"},"810":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity-24","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","content":"foundations"},"811":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity-25","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model-capacity","content":"taxonomy"},"812":{"id":"/docs/glossary/architecture","page_id":"/docs/glossary/architecture","type":"page","content":"Architecture","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/architecture"},"813":{"id":"/docs/glossary/architecture-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/architecture","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/architecture","content":"The blueprint that defines how a model's layers, modules, and data flow connect during inference."},"814":{"id":"/docs/glossary/architecture-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/architecture","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/architecture#heading-0","content":"Architecture"},"815":{"id":"/docs/glossary/architecture-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/architecture","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/architecture#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"816":{"id":"/docs/glossary/architecture-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/architecture","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/architecture#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"817":{"id":"/docs/glossary/architecture-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/architecture","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/architecture#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"818":{"id":"/docs/glossary/architecture-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/architecture","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/architecture#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"819":{"id":"/docs/glossary/architecture-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/architecture","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/architecture#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"820":{"id":"/docs/glossary/architecture-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/architecture","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/architecture#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"821":{"id":"/docs/glossary/architecture-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/architecture","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/architecture#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"822":{"id":"/docs/glossary/architecture-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/architecture","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/architecture#heading-8","content":"References"},"823":{"id":"/docs/glossary/architecture-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/architecture","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/architecture#Architecture","content":"The blueprint that defines how a model's layers, modules, and data flow connect during inference.\n\nArchitecture\nThe blueprint that defines how a model's layers, modules, and data flow connect during inference.\nArchitecture is the structural recipe—how tensors move through repeated modules—not any one trained set of weights, which people often conflate with specific checkpoints or product families.\nWhat It Is\nAn architecture specifies layer types, connectivity, and the order of computation. Transformers, U-Net diffusion stacks, and mixture-of-experts layouts are architectures. Many model checkpoints can instantiate the same architecture at different scales.\nWhy It Matters\nKnowing the architecture tells you which modules to expect, how memory scales with sequence length, and which family pages in this atlas apply before you open a specific checkpoint. Ask \"what repeats in the stack?\" to spot the architecture; ask \"which checkpoint am I running?\" to spot the model.\nSimple Example\nA decoder-only transformer architecture stacks token embeddings, repeated attention-plus-FFN blocks, and a final language-model head. GPT-2, Llama, and many chat models share that shape even when widths and depths differ.\nWhere It Appears\nArchitecture shows up in model cards, scaling-law papers, and module pages that explain attention variants. Related links below connect to major model families and structural concepts in this atlas.\nCommon Confusions\nArchitecture is broader than a single module: attention is a module inside many architectures. It is also narrower than \"model\": you can train many models on one architecture. A model family name often implies an architecture but may bundle training data and tooling too.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences"},"824":{"id":"/docs/glossary/architecture-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/architecture","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/architecture","content":"model architecture"},"825":{"id":"/docs/glossary/architecture-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/architecture","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/architecture","content":"neural architecture"},"826":{"id":"/docs/glossary/architecture-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/architecture","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/architecture","content":"network architecture"},"827":{"id":"/docs/glossary/architecture-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/architecture","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/architecture","content":"taxonomy"},"828":{"id":"/docs/glossary/architecture-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/architecture","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/architecture","content":"glossary taxonomy"},"829":{"id":"/docs/glossary/architecture-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/architecture","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/architecture","content":"atlas taxonomy"},"830":{"id":"/docs/glossary/architecture-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/architecture","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/architecture","content":"taxonomy glossary"},"831":{"id":"/docs/glossary/architecture-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/architecture","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/architecture","content":"cross-family taxonomy"},"832":{"id":"/docs/glossary/architecture-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/architecture","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/architecture","content":"foundations"},"833":{"id":"/docs/glossary/architecture-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/architecture","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/architecture","content":"foundational concepts"},"834":{"id":"/docs/glossary/architecture-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/architecture","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/architecture","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"835":{"id":"/docs/glossary/architecture-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/architecture","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/architecture","content":"core vocabulary"},"836":{"id":"/docs/glossary/architecture-23","page_id":"/docs/glossary/architecture","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/architecture","content":"taxonomy"},"837":{"id":"/docs/glossary/architecture-24","page_id":"/docs/glossary/architecture","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/architecture","content":"foundations"},"838":{"id":"/docs/glossary/patch","page_id":"/docs/glossary/patch","type":"page","content":"Patch","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/patch"},"839":{"id":"/docs/glossary/patch-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/patch","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/patch","content":"A fixed-size chunk of input data—pixels, spectrogram frames, or grouped tokens—that an encoder turns into a representation vector."},"840":{"id":"/docs/glossary/patch-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/patch","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/patch#heading-0","content":"Patch"},"841":{"id":"/docs/glossary/patch-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/patch","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/patch#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"842":{"id":"/docs/glossary/patch-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/patch","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/patch#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"843":{"id":"/docs/glossary/patch-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/patch","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/patch#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"844":{"id":"/docs/glossary/patch-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/patch","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/patch#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"845":{"id":"/docs/glossary/patch-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/patch","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/patch#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"846":{"id":"/docs/glossary/patch-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/patch","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/patch#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"847":{"id":"/docs/glossary/patch-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/patch","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/patch#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"848":{"id":"/docs/glossary/patch-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/patch","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/patch#heading-8","content":"References"},"849":{"id":"/docs/glossary/patch-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/patch","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/patch#Patch","content":"A fixed-size chunk of input data—pixels, spectrogram frames, or grouped tokens—that an encoder turns into a representation vector.\n\nPatch\nA fixed-size chunk of input data—pixels, spectrogram frames, or grouped tokens—that an encoder turns into a representation vector.\nA patch is the smallest spatial or sequential unit the model treats as one input item before stacking layers, mapped by encoders into representation vectors.\nWhat It Is\nIn vision transformers, an image is split into a grid of non-overlapping or lightly overlapping patches; each patch becomes a token-like vector after a linear projection. In audio or video, analogous windows play the same role. Patches sit between raw modality data and the internal representation tensors that deeper blocks consume.\nWhy It Matters\nPatch granularity controls compute and inductive bias: smaller patches preserve detail but increase sequence length; larger patches compress context. Naming patches separately from latents and from full representations keeps vision, diffusion, and multimodal docs aligned with how encoders are drawn.\nSimple Example\nA 224×224 image with 16×16 pixel patches yields a 14×14 grid—196 patch tokens before the class token. Each patch embedding is a representation of that local region, not the whole image.\nWhere It Appears\nPatch tokenization appears in ViT-style encoders, latent diffusion autoencoders, and multimodal models that align image patches with text tokens. The modality glossary explains which channels use patches; representation explains the vectors they become.\nCommon Confusions\nA patch is not a latent: patches are input-side chunks, while a latent is a compressed internal code after encoding. A patch is also not a token in the language-model sense unless the architecture explicitly equates patch embeddings with discrete token IDs. Patch size is not model capacity—it is an input tiling choice.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nAsk how the raw input is tiled before the first transformer block—that tiling unit is the patch story."},"850":{"id":"/docs/glossary/patch-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/patch","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/patch","content":"image patch"},"851":{"id":"/docs/glossary/patch-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/patch","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/patch","content":"vision patch"},"852":{"id":"/docs/glossary/patch-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/patch","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/patch","content":"token patch"},"853":{"id":"/docs/glossary/patch-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/patch","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/patch","content":"foundations"},"854":{"id":"/docs/glossary/patch-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/patch","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/patch","content":"foundational concepts"},"855":{"id":"/docs/glossary/patch-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/patch","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/patch","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"856":{"id":"/docs/glossary/patch-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/patch","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/patch","content":"core vocabulary"},"857":{"id":"/docs/glossary/patch-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/patch","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/patch","content":"taxonomy"},"858":{"id":"/docs/glossary/patch-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/patch","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/patch","content":"glossary taxonomy"},"859":{"id":"/docs/glossary/patch-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/patch","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/patch","content":"atlas taxonomy"},"860":{"id":"/docs/glossary/patch-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/patch","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/patch","content":"taxonomy glossary"},"861":{"id":"/docs/glossary/patch-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/patch","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/patch","content":"cross-family taxonomy"},"862":{"id":"/docs/glossary/patch-23","page_id":"/docs/glossary/patch","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/patch","content":"foundations"},"863":{"id":"/docs/glossary/patch-24","page_id":"/docs/glossary/patch","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/patch","content":"taxonomy"},"864":{"id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","page_id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","type":"page","content":"Perplexity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/perplexity"},"865":{"id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","content":"A standard language-model evaluation metric: exponentiated average cross-entropy over tokens, lower is better when comparing models on the same corpus."},"866":{"id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/perplexity#heading-0","content":"Perplexity"},"867":{"id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/perplexity#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"868":{"id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/perplexity#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"869":{"id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/perplexity#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"870":{"id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/perplexity#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"871":{"id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/perplexity#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"872":{"id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/perplexity#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"873":{"id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/perplexity#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"874":{"id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/perplexity#heading-8","content":"References"},"875":{"id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/perplexity#Perplexity","content":"A standard language-model evaluation metric: exponentiated average cross-entropy over tokens, lower is better when comparing models on the same corpus.\n\nPerplexity\nA standard language-model evaluation metric: exponentiated average cross-entropy over tokens, lower is better when comparing models on the same corpus.\nPerplexity summarizes how surprised a model is by held-out text as exp(average cross-entropy), so lower scores mean higher probability on true continuations.\nWhat It Is\nGiven a test corpus, perplexity averages the negative log-likelihood the model assigns to each token (via softmax over logits), then exponentiates. It is not a task accuracy score—it measures probabilistic fit. Tokenization, vocabulary, and dataset domain all affect the number, so comparisons require matched setups.\nWhy It Matters\nPerplexity is the workhorse metric for pretraining and compression benchmarks because it tracks how well next-token distributions match data. It connects directly to the token chain: logits become probabilities through softmax, and cross-entropy (linked to entropy) aggregates those probabilities into one scalar for monitoring generalization.\nSimple Example\nIf a model assigns 0.5 probability to each correct next token on average, cross-entropy is about 0.69 nats and perplexity is about 2—roughly as uncertain as choosing uniformly among two tokens. Halving perplexity means the model is substantially more confident on the evaluation text.\nWhere It Appears\nPretraining dashboards, academic LM benchmarks, and model cards reporting validation perplexity. Generalization pages describe whether patterns transfer; perplexity quantifies probabilistic transfer on language corpora when the evaluation set is truly held out.\nCommon Confusions\nLower perplexity does not guarantee better instruction following or safety—that is alignment and task design. Perplexity on training data can look excellent while test perplexity reveals overfitting. Do not compare perplexity across different tokenizers without caution.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nTreat perplexity as exponentiated average surprise per token—always check which corpus and tokenizer produced the score."},"876":{"id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","content":"Perplexity"},"877":{"id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","content":"PPL"},"878":{"id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","content":"cross-entropy perplexity"},"879":{"id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","content":"language model perplexity"},"880":{"id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","content":"foundations"},"881":{"id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","content":"foundational concepts"},"882":{"id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"883":{"id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","content":"core vocabulary"},"884":{"id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","content":"taxonomy"},"885":{"id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","content":"glossary taxonomy"},"886":{"id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","content":"atlas taxonomy"},"887":{"id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","content":"taxonomy glossary"},"888":{"id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity-23","page_id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","content":"cross-family taxonomy"},"889":{"id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity-24","page_id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","content":"foundations"},"890":{"id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity-25","page_id":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/perplexity","content":"taxonomy"},"891":{"id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","page_id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","type":"page","content":"Diffusion Model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"url":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model"},"892":{"id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","content":"A generative model family that learns to reverse a noise corruption process through many iterative denoising steps."},"893":{"id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"url":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model#heading-0","content":"Diffusion Model"},"894":{"id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"url":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"895":{"id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"url":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"896":{"id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"url":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"897":{"id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"url":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model#heading-4","content":"Common Confusions"},"898":{"id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"url":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model#heading-5","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"899":{"id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"url":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model#heading-6","content":"Tags"},"900":{"id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"url":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model#heading-7","content":"References"},"901":{"id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model#Diffusion Model","content":"A generative model family that learns to reverse a noise corruption process through many iterative denoising steps.\n\nDiffusion Model\nA generative model family that learns to reverse a noise corruption process through many iterative denoising steps.\nDiffusion models corrupt data with noise during training, then learn to walk backward through that noise schedule at inference—often in latent space with conditioning—until a clean generative sample emerges.\nWhat It Is\nA diffusion model trains on a forward process that gradually adds noise to data, then learns a network that predicts and removes that noise step by step at inference. Each denoising update refines a latent or pixel tensor until a coherent sample appears. The family name covers score-based, variance-preserving, and flow-matching variants that share the iterative denoising loop rather than a single architecture block recipe.\nWhy It Matters\nDiffusion models power many image, audio, and video generators and sit beside autoregressive decoders as a major generative paradigm. Knowing the family separates denoising-based sampling from token-by-token decoding and connects to latent representations and conditioning signals used at each step. The architecture page places diffusion among other model families; this page is the dedicated reference for iterative denoising generators.\nSimple Example\nA latent diffusion image model starts from Gaussian noise in a compressed latent grid, runs forty denoising steps with a U-Net or transformer denoiser conditioned on a text embedding, then decodes the final latent through a VAE to pixels.\nCommon Confusions\nDiffusion model is a model family and sampling paradigm, not a synonym for any single checkpoint or U-Net shape. Denoising generation describes the iterative output loop; diffusion models are the most common implementation of that loop but not the only one. Diffusion also differs from autoregressive generation: denoising updates the full spatial or channel tensor each step rather than appending one discrete token.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences"},"902":{"id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","content":"diffusion models"},"903":{"id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","content":"diffusion architecture"},"904":{"id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","content":"denoising diffusion"},"905":{"id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","content":"taxonomy"},"906":{"id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","content":"glossary taxonomy"},"907":{"id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","content":"atlas taxonomy"},"908":{"id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","content":"taxonomy glossary"},"909":{"id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","content":"cross-family taxonomy"},"910":{"id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","content":"model-family"},"911":{"id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","content":"model families"},"912":{"id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","content":"architecture families"},"913":{"id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","content":"model family"},"914":{"id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","content":"taxonomy"},"915":{"id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model-23","page_id":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/diffusion-model","content":"model-family"},"916":{"id":"/docs/glossary/representation","page_id":"/docs/glossary/representation","type":"page","content":"Representation","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/representation"},"917":{"id":"/docs/glossary/representation-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/representation","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/representation","content":"An internal encoding of input data that downstream layers or tasks use instead of raw features."},"918":{"id":"/docs/glossary/representation-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/representation","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/representation#heading-0","content":"Representation"},"919":{"id":"/docs/glossary/representation-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/representation","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/representation#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"920":{"id":"/docs/glossary/representation-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/representation","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/representation#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"921":{"id":"/docs/glossary/representation-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/representation","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/representation#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"922":{"id":"/docs/glossary/representation-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/representation","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/representation#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"923":{"id":"/docs/glossary/representation-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/representation","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/representation#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"924":{"id":"/docs/glossary/representation-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/representation","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/representation#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"925":{"id":"/docs/glossary/representation-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/representation","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/representation#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"926":{"id":"/docs/glossary/representation-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/representation","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/representation#heading-8","content":"References"},"927":{"id":"/docs/glossary/representation-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/representation","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/representation#Representation","content":"An internal encoding of input data that downstream layers or tasks use instead of raw features.\n\nRepresentation\nAn internal encoding of input data that downstream layers or tasks use instead of raw features.\nA representation is the learned internal form of data after encoding—vectors that capture structure for later layers, whether or not exposed as a standalone embedding API.\nWhat It Is\nRepresentations are tensors produced inside the model: hidden states, latent codes, or pooled vectors used for classification, generation, or retrieval. They sit between raw modality inputs and task heads. Multiple modules may read and write representations across depth.\nWhy It Matters\nClear representation language helps you compare transfer learning, contrastive training, and generative latent spaces without conflating them with tokenizer outputs or public embedding products. Ask where in the stack the vector lives: input lookup (often called embedding) versus hidden state after layers (representation).\nSimple Example\nAfter a transformer block processes token embeddings, the hidden state at each position is a representation. A sentence classifier might pool those states; a generative model feeds them to the next block and the output head.\nWhere It Appears\nRepresentation appears in papers on self-supervised learning, multimodal alignment, and links from modality to generative model when discussing latents used for sampling.\nCommon Confusions\nRepresentation versus embedding: an embedding often means a lookup from discrete IDs to vectors at the input boundary, while representation is the broader term for internal encodings at any depth. Not every embedding table output is the final representation used for downstream tasks. Representation is also not modality—modality names the data channel; representation names the encoded form inside the network.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences"},"928":{"id":"/docs/glossary/representation-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/representation","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/representation","content":"learned representation"},"929":{"id":"/docs/glossary/representation-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/representation","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/representation","content":"feature representation"},"930":{"id":"/docs/glossary/representation-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/representation","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/representation","content":"latent representation"},"931":{"id":"/docs/glossary/representation-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/representation","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/representation","content":"taxonomy"},"932":{"id":"/docs/glossary/representation-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/representation","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/representation","content":"glossary taxonomy"},"933":{"id":"/docs/glossary/representation-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/representation","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/representation","content":"atlas taxonomy"},"934":{"id":"/docs/glossary/representation-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/representation","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/representation","content":"taxonomy glossary"},"935":{"id":"/docs/glossary/representation-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/representation","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/representation","content":"cross-family taxonomy"},"936":{"id":"/docs/glossary/representation-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/representation","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/representation","content":"foundations"},"937":{"id":"/docs/glossary/representation-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/representation","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/representation","content":"foundational concepts"},"938":{"id":"/docs/glossary/representation-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/representation","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/representation","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"939":{"id":"/docs/glossary/representation-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/representation","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/representation","content":"core vocabulary"},"940":{"id":"/docs/glossary/representation-23","page_id":"/docs/glossary/representation","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/representation","content":"taxonomy"},"941":{"id":"/docs/glossary/representation-24","page_id":"/docs/glossary/representation","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/representation","content":"foundations"},"942":{"id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","page_id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","type":"page","content":"Loss Function","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/loss-function"},"943":{"id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","content":"A scalar score that measures how wrong the model's predictions are so training knows which direction to improve."},"944":{"id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/loss-function#heading-0","content":"Loss Function"},"945":{"id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/loss-function#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"946":{"id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/loss-function#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"947":{"id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/loss-function#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"948":{"id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/loss-function#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"949":{"id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/loss-function#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"950":{"id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/loss-function#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"951":{"id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/loss-function#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"952":{"id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/loss-function#heading-8","content":"References"},"953":{"id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/loss-function#Loss Function","content":"A scalar score that measures how wrong the model's predictions are so training knows which direction to improve.\n\nLoss Function\nA scalar score that measures how wrong the model's predictions are so training knows which direction to improve.\nA loss function compares model outputs to targets and returns one scalar whose gradients drive parameter updates during training.\nWhat It Is\nThe loss (also called the objective or training loss) aggregates per-example errors into one differentiable scalar. For language models, cross-entropy between predicted next-token probabilities and the true token id is standard. Regression tasks might use mean squared error. The loss sits at the root of the computational graph so backpropagation can reach every parameter that influenced the prediction.\nWhy It Matters\nOptimizers do not read raw logits or activations—they minimize the loss. The choice of loss shapes what the model learns to prioritize: cross-entropy penalizes confident wrong tokens heavily, while other objectives emphasize ranking, contrast, or auxiliary tasks. Monitoring loss curves is the first signal that training is converging, diverging, or stuck.\nSimple Example\nSuppose a three-token vocabulary and the model assigns probabilities [0.7, 0.2, 0.1] while the correct token is index 0. Cross-entropy loss is roughly −log(0.7), a small positive number. If the model instead gave 0.01 probability to the correct token, the loss jumps because −log(0.01) is much larger.\nWhere It Appears\nPyTorch `nn.CrossEntropyLoss`, TensorFlow/Keras `SparseCategoricalCrossentropy`, and JAX `optax.softmax_cross_entropy` all implement the same idea for classification and next-token prediction. Distinctive chain phrase: scalar training objective summed over the batch before backward().\nCommon Confusions\nLoss is not the same as accuracy or perplexity—those are evaluation metrics derived from predictions, while loss is what gradients differentiate during training. A model can have low training loss but poor generalization (overfitting). Loss also differs from regularization terms, which are sometimes added to the objective but serve a different purpose than fit-to-labels error.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nLoss turns predictions and targets into one number to minimize. Backpropagation starts from that scalar; the optimizer uses the resulting gradients to update parameters."},"954":{"id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","content":"loss"},"955":{"id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","content":"objective function"},"956":{"id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","content":"training loss"},"957":{"id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","content":"token-to-probability-chain"},"958":{"id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","content":"token to probability chain"},"959":{"id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","content":"phase 2 probability chain"},"960":{"id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","content":"foundations probability path"},"961":{"id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","content":"foundations"},"962":{"id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","content":"foundational concepts"},"963":{"id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"964":{"id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","content":"core vocabulary"},"965":{"id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","content":"token-to-probability-chain"},"966":{"id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function-23","page_id":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/loss-function","content":"foundations"},"967":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm","type":"page","content":"RMSNorm","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm"},"968":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm","content":"Per-token root-mean-square scaling that rescales each hidden vector without mean centering, as used in many modern decoder transformers."},"969":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm#heading-0","content":"RMSNorm"},"970":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"971":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"972":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"973":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm#heading-4","content":"Formula And Symbols"},"974":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"975":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"976":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"977":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm#heading-8","content":"References"},"978":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm#RMSNorm","content":"Per-token root-mean-square scaling that rescales each hidden vector without mean centering, as used in many modern decoder transformers.\n\nRMSNorm\nPer-token root-mean-square scaling that rescales each hidden vector without mean centering, as used in many modern decoder transformers.\nRMSNorm rescales each token's hidden vector by its root mean square spread without subtracting the mean, then applies learned per-feature gain before the next sublayer runs.\nWhat It Is\nRoot mean square normalization (RMSNorm) rescales one token's hidden vector by dividing each feature by the root mean square of those features, then applying a learned per-feature scale. Unlike layer norm, it skips subtracting the mean across features. Statistics are still computed per position, which fits decoder transformers that process one token vector at a time inside each block.\nWhy It Matters\nMany recent large language models—including Llama-class stacks—use RMSNorm instead of layer norm because dropping mean centering saves compute while keeping activations in a stable range. The choice matters when you read model cards or compare training recipes: RMSNorm is not a different placement strategy, it is a lighter rescaling rule inside the same pre-norm block pattern.\nSimple Example\nAfter self-attention, one token vector might have features with different magnitudes. RMSNorm measures the root mean square spread across those features, divides each feature by that stabilized scale, then multiplies by learned gain. The feed-forward network receives a vector whose overall magnitude sits in a predictable band without shifting every feature toward zero mean first.\nFormula And Symbols\nThe rescale below applies to one token position. Each symbol names a quantity in that vector, not a batch-wide statistic.\nCommon Confusions\nRMSNorm is not layer norm with a different name: layer norm subtracts the feature mean and uses both learned scale and shift, while RMSNorm only divides by root mean square and typically applies learned scale alone. RMSNorm is also not batch norm—it never pools statistics across examples. When a model card says RMSNorm, expect the lighter no-centering rescale rather than full mean-and-variance normalization.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences"},"979":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm","content":"RMS Norm"},"980":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm","content":"root mean square normalization"},"981":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm","content":"RMSNorm"},"982":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm","content":"foundations"},"983":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm","content":"foundational concepts"},"984":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"985":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm","content":"core vocabulary"},"986":{"id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/rmsnorm","content":"foundations"},"987":{"id":"/docs/glossary/context-window","page_id":"/docs/glossary/context-window","type":"page","content":"Context window","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/context-window"},"988":{"id":"/docs/glossary/context-window-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/context-window","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/context-window","content":"The maximum number of tokens a model can attend over in one forward pass, distinct from training sequence length and how many tokens it may emit in a session."},"989":{"id":"/docs/glossary/context-window-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/context-window","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/context-window#heading-0","content":"Context window"},"990":{"id":"/docs/glossary/context-window-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/context-window","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/context-window#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"991":{"id":"/docs/glossary/context-window-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/context-window","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/context-window#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"992":{"id":"/docs/glossary/context-window-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/context-window","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/context-window#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"993":{"id":"/docs/glossary/context-window-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/context-window","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/context-window#heading-4","content":"Common Confusions"},"994":{"id":"/docs/glossary/context-window-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/context-window","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/context-window#heading-5","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"995":{"id":"/docs/glossary/context-window-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/context-window","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/context-window#heading-6","content":"Tags"},"996":{"id":"/docs/glossary/context-window-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/context-window","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/context-window#heading-7","content":"References"},"997":{"id":"/docs/glossary/context-window-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/context-window","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/context-window#Context window","content":"The maximum number of tokens a model can attend over in one forward pass, distinct from training sequence length and how many tokens it may emit in a session.\n\nContext window\nThe maximum number of tokens a model can attend over in one forward pass, distinct from training sequence length and how many tokens it may emit in a session.\nContext window is the maximum number of tokens attention can see in one forward pass, separate from training sequence length and from how many tokens a session may generate.\nWhat It Is\nA context window—also called context length or max context—is the cap on how many tokens the model can read and attend over in a single forward pass. Every prompt token, document chunk, and previously generated token that stays inside attention counts toward that limit. When the window fills, older tokens fall out of the active attention range unless the serving stack summarizes or truncates them. The window is a hard structural bound on simultaneous visibility, not a rough preference about how much text is convenient to paste in.\nWhy It Matters\nContext window is easy to confuse with two nearby limits. Training length is the longest sequence the model saw during pretraining or fine-tuning; a model may train on eight-thousand-token examples yet ship with a larger inference window after extension techniques. Generation budget is how many new tokens the system allows the model to write in one reply or session, which can be smaller than the window if product policy caps output. Memory and attention cost also grow with window size, so the advertised limit reflects what the stack can run reliably, not unlimited recall.\nSimple Example\nSuppose a model advertises a 128k context window. You can place on the order of 128,000 tokens—system instructions, retrieved notes, and prior chat turns—into one prompt block that attention can see at once. If you keep chatting until active history exceeds that count, the earliest tokens stop participating in attention unless the client drops or compresses them. You might still ask the model to write only five hundred new tokens, which is a generation budget choice separate from the 128k visibility cap.\nCommon Confusions\nA larger context window does not automatically mean the model was trained on equally long sequences; extension methods can stretch inference beyond original training spans. Context window is also not the same as total session storage in a chat product, which may keep transcripts on disk while only the latest slice fits inside model attention. Finally, max context differs from output token limits: you can have room to read a long document yet still be capped on how many tokens the assistant may generate in one response.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences"},"998":{"id":"/docs/glossary/context-window-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/context-window","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/context-window","content":"context length"},"999":{"id":"/docs/glossary/context-window-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/context-window","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/context-window","content":"sequence length limit"},"1000":{"id":"/docs/glossary/context-window-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/context-window","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/context-window","content":"max context"},"1001":{"id":"/docs/glossary/context-window-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/context-window","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/context-window","content":"foundations"},"1002":{"id":"/docs/glossary/context-window-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/context-window","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/context-window","content":"foundational concepts"},"1003":{"id":"/docs/glossary/context-window-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/context-window","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/context-window","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"1004":{"id":"/docs/glossary/context-window-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/context-window","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/context-window","content":"core vocabulary"},"1005":{"id":"/docs/glossary/context-window-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/context-window","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/context-window","content":"foundations"},"1006":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model","type":"page","content":"Model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/model"},"1007":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model","content":"A trained machine learning system that maps inputs to outputs using learned parameters."},"1008":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/model#heading-0","content":"Model"},"1009":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/model#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"1010":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/model#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"1011":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/model#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"1012":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/model#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"1013":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/model#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"1014":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/model#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"1015":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/model#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"1016":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/model#heading-8","content":"References"},"1017":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model#Model","content":"A trained machine learning system that maps inputs to outputs using learned parameters.\n\nModel\nA trained machine learning system that maps inputs to outputs using learned parameters.\nA model is the trained artifact—weights plus the inference procedure that maps inputs to outputs for a defined task.\nWhat It Is\nIn this reference, a model is the end product you run at inference time. It includes learned parameters and the forward pass that applies them. Checkpoints, Hugging Face repos, and API endpoints all refer to concrete model instances, not abstract design patterns.\nWhy It Matters\nSeparating model from architecture, module, and component helps you compare releases, trace bugs, and search the atlas without conflating a family name with a specific trained checkpoint. When a paper says \"we train a model,\" it usually means they optimized weights for a fixed architecture and dataset—not that they invented a new layer type.\nSimple Example\nGPT-2 124M is a model: a particular set of weights trained with a transformer architecture. The architecture page explains how layers connect; the model page names the artifact you load or call.\nWhere It Appears\nModel appears in release notes, evaluation tables, serving configs, and family overviews. Taxonomy pages for architecture, modality, and foundation model sit one level below or beside this term.\nCommon Confusions\nA model is not the same as an architecture: many checkpoints can share one architecture. A model is also not a single layer or attention block—those are modules and components inside the architecture.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences"},"1018":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model","content":"ML model"},"1019":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model","content":"machine learning model"},"1020":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model","content":"neural network model"},"1021":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model","content":"taxonomy"},"1022":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model","content":"glossary taxonomy"},"1023":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model","content":"atlas taxonomy"},"1024":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model","content":"taxonomy glossary"},"1025":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model","content":"cross-family taxonomy"},"1026":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model","content":"foundations"},"1027":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model","content":"foundational concepts"},"1028":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"1029":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model","content":"core vocabulary"},"1030":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-23","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model","content":"taxonomy"},"1031":{"id":"/docs/glossary/model-24","page_id":"/docs/glossary/model","tags":["taxonomy","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/model","content":"foundations"},"1032":{"id":"/docs/glossary/softmax","page_id":"/docs/glossary/softmax","type":"page","content":"Softmax","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/softmax"},"1033":{"id":"/docs/glossary/softmax-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/softmax","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/softmax","content":"A function that turns a vector of logits into a probability distribution that sums to one."},"1034":{"id":"/docs/glossary/softmax-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/softmax","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/softmax#heading-0","content":"Softmax"},"1035":{"id":"/docs/glossary/softmax-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/softmax","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/softmax#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"1036":{"id":"/docs/glossary/softmax-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/softmax","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/softmax#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"1037":{"id":"/docs/glossary/softmax-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/softmax","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/softmax#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"1038":{"id":"/docs/glossary/softmax-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/softmax","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/softmax#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"1039":{"id":"/docs/glossary/softmax-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/softmax","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/softmax#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"1040":{"id":"/docs/glossary/softmax-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/softmax","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/softmax#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"1041":{"id":"/docs/glossary/softmax-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/softmax","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/softmax#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"1042":{"id":"/docs/glossary/softmax-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/softmax","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/softmax#heading-8","content":"References"},"1043":{"id":"/docs/glossary/softmax-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/softmax","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/softmax#Softmax","content":"A function that turns a vector of logits into a probability distribution that sums to one.\n\nSoftmax\nA function that turns a vector of logits into a probability distribution that sums to one.\nSoftmax converts logits into nonnegative probabilities that sum to 1 across the vocabulary—the standard step from raw scores to interpretable chances.\nWhat It Is\nSoftmax is the usual final normalization for multiclass outputs in language models. Given a logits vector z, it returns probabilities p_i proportional to exp(z_i), divided by the sum across all classes.\nWhy It Matters\nNext-token sampling reads softmax probabilities. Cross-entropy training compares softmax outputs to target tokens. Any discussion of model confidence, entropy, or temperature assumes you understand this mapping from logits to a distribution.\nSimple Example\nWith logits [2.0, 1.0, 0.0], softmax assigns the largest mass to index 0 because exp(2) dominates, but all three entries receive strictly positive probability. Dividing logits by temperature before softmax sharpens or flattens that distribution.\nWhere It Appears\nAutoregressive transformers apply softmax along the vocabulary dimension of the logits tensor at each position. Frameworks expose it as nn.Softmax, jax.nn.softmax, or fused kernels inside sampling loops. Distinctive chain phrase: vocabulary softmax normalization at decode time.\nCommon Confusions\nSoftmax is not the same as a single activation inside a hidden layer—those may be ReLU or GELU. Softmax also differs from sigmoid, which handles binary probabilities. Applying softmax twice does not generally recover the original logits.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nIf you can read one softmax formula, you can follow temperature and entropy pages next—they all manipulate the same probability vector."},"1044":{"id":"/docs/glossary/softmax-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/softmax","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/softmax","content":"softmax function"},"1045":{"id":"/docs/glossary/softmax-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/softmax","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/softmax","content":"softmax layer"},"1046":{"id":"/docs/glossary/softmax-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/softmax","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/softmax","content":"token-to-probability-chain"},"1047":{"id":"/docs/glossary/softmax-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/softmax","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/softmax","content":"token to probability chain"},"1048":{"id":"/docs/glossary/softmax-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/softmax","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/softmax","content":"phase 2 probability chain"},"1049":{"id":"/docs/glossary/softmax-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/softmax","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/softmax","content":"foundations probability path"},"1050":{"id":"/docs/glossary/softmax-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/softmax","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/softmax","content":"foundations"},"1051":{"id":"/docs/glossary/softmax-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/softmax","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/softmax","content":"foundational concepts"},"1052":{"id":"/docs/glossary/softmax-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/softmax","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/softmax","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"1053":{"id":"/docs/glossary/softmax-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/softmax","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/softmax","content":"core vocabulary"},"1054":{"id":"/docs/glossary/softmax-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/softmax","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/softmax","content":"token-to-probability-chain"},"1055":{"id":"/docs/glossary/softmax-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/softmax","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/softmax","content":"foundations"},"1056":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alignment","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alignment","type":"page","content":"Alignment","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/alignment"},"1057":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alignment-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alignment","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/alignment","content":"Post-training steps that steer a model toward helpful, honest, and policy-compliant behavior—often via preference data, reward models, or safety filters."},"1058":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alignment-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alignment","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/alignment#heading-0","content":"Alignment"},"1059":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alignment-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alignment","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/alignment#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"1060":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alignment-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alignment","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/alignment#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"1061":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alignment-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alignment","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/alignment#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"1062":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alignment-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alignment","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/alignment#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"1063":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alignment-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alignment","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/alignment#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"1064":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alignment-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alignment","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/alignment#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"1065":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alignment-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alignment","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/alignment#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"1066":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alignment-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alignment","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/alignment#heading-8","content":"References"},"1067":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alignment-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alignment","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/alignment#Alignment","content":"Post-training steps that steer a model toward helpful, honest, and policy-compliant behavior—often via preference data, reward models, or safety filters.\n\nAlignment\nPost-training steps that steer a model toward helpful, honest, and policy-compliant behavior—often via preference data, reward models, or safety filters.\nAlignment layers human or policy preferences on top of a pretrained generator through reward models, preference optimization, and runtime guardrails that sit after the core loss-and-optimizer training loop.\nWhat It Is\nAlignment is the family of post-training methods—supervised fine-tuning on demonstrations, reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF), direct preference optimization, and constitutional or rule-based critics—that nudge model behavior without replacing the base architecture. Safety classifiers and system prompts are inference-time alignment tools that complement weight updates.\nWhy It Matters\nCapacity and generalization describe what a model can learn from data; alignment describes whose preferences win after that learning. Product teams need both stories: a high-capacity model can still violate policy if alignment is weak, and strong filters cannot fix a base model that never learned the task.\nSimple Example\nA chat model is pretrained on web text, then fine-tuned on helpful assistant transcripts, then updated with a reward model that prefers concise, safe answers over rambling or toxic ones. At serve time, a moderation API blocks categories the reward model never saw.\nWhere It Appears\nInstruction-tuned language models, image generators with safety filters, and enterprise deployments that combine RLHF checkpoints with allow-lists. Conditioning explains runtime control signals; model capacity and generalization explain whether the base model had room to absorb preferences.\nCommon Confusions\nAlignment is not the same as architecture design or tokenizer choice. It is also not identical to evaluation metrics such as perplexity—those measure prediction quality, not policy fit. RLHF is one alignment method, not the whole field.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nAsk which preference signal is applied after pretraining—demonstrations, rewards, rules, or filters—and whether it changes weights or only inference."},"1068":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alignment-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alignment","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/alignment","content":"Alignment"},"1069":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alignment-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alignment","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/alignment","content":"RLHF"},"1070":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alignment-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alignment","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/alignment","content":"preference alignment"},"1071":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alignment-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alignment","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/alignment","content":"safety alignment"},"1072":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alignment-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alignment","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/alignment","content":"foundations"},"1073":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alignment-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alignment","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/alignment","content":"foundational concepts"},"1074":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alignment-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alignment","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/alignment","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"1075":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alignment-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alignment","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/alignment","content":"core vocabulary"},"1076":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alignment-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alignment","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/alignment","content":"taxonomy"},"1077":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alignment-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alignment","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/alignment","content":"glossary taxonomy"},"1078":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alignment-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alignment","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/alignment","content":"atlas taxonomy"},"1079":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alignment-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alignment","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/alignment","content":"taxonomy glossary"},"1080":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alignment-23","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alignment","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/alignment","content":"cross-family taxonomy"},"1081":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alignment-24","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alignment","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/alignment","content":"foundations"},"1082":{"id":"/docs/glossary/alignment-25","page_id":"/docs/glossary/alignment","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/alignment","content":"taxonomy"},"1083":{"id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network","page_id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network","type":"page","content":"Feed-forward network","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network"},"1084":{"id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network","content":"The position-wise dense transform that refines each token's hidden vector after attention in a transformer block."},"1085":{"id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network#heading-0","content":"Feed-forward network"},"1086":{"id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"1087":{"id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"1088":{"id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"1089":{"id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network#heading-4","content":"Common Confusions"},"1090":{"id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network#heading-5","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"1091":{"id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network#heading-6","content":"Tags"},"1092":{"id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network#heading-7","content":"References"},"1093":{"id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network#Feed-forward network","content":"The position-wise dense transform that refines each token's hidden vector after attention in a transformer block.\n\nFeed-forward network\nThe position-wise dense transform that refines each token's hidden vector after attention in a transformer block.\nA feed-forward network is the per-token MLP that follows attention in each transformer block, refining each position's hidden state without mixing across the sequence.\nWhat It Is\nA feed-forward network (FFN), also called an MLP block, is a small two-layer perceptron applied independently to every token position. After attention mixes information across positions, the FFN takes each position's hidden vector, expands it through an intermediate width, applies a nonlinearity, and projects back to the model width. The same weights run at every position—only the input vector changes.\nWhy It Matters\nAttention decides what each position can read from the sequence; the FFN decides how to transform what was read into richer features. Most transformer blocks alternate these two steps, so recognizing the FFN slot helps you read architecture diagrams and spot when a model swaps a dense MLP for a mixture-of-experts layer while keeping the block shape.\nSimple Example\nImagine a decoder block after self-attention has updated every word vector. The FFN runs the same recipe on each vector: multiply by a wide weight matrix, apply a gated or ReLU-style activation, then multiply by a second matrix back to hidden size. Position three's vector never mixes with position seven inside the FFN—that mixing already happened in attention.\nCommon Confusions\nThe FFN is not attention: it does not look at other tokens. It is also not the language-model head at the stack top—that head maps final hidden states to vocabulary logits. A mixture-of-experts layer replaces the dense FFN with routed expert MLPs but still sits in the same block slot after attention.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences"},"1094":{"id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network","content":"FFN"},"1095":{"id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network","content":"feedforward network"},"1096":{"id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network","content":"MLP block"},"1097":{"id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network","content":"foundations"},"1098":{"id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network","content":"foundational concepts"},"1099":{"id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"1100":{"id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network","content":"core vocabulary"},"1101":{"id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/feed-forward-network","content":"foundations"},"1102":{"id":"/docs/glossary/parameter","page_id":"/docs/glossary/parameter","type":"page","content":"Parameter","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/parameter"},"1103":{"id":"/docs/glossary/parameter-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/parameter","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/parameter","content":"A learnable numeric value stored in the model weights that training updates to fit data."},"1104":{"id":"/docs/glossary/parameter-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/parameter","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/parameter#heading-0","content":"Parameter"},"1105":{"id":"/docs/glossary/parameter-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/parameter","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/parameter#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"1106":{"id":"/docs/glossary/parameter-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/parameter","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/parameter#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"1107":{"id":"/docs/glossary/parameter-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/parameter","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/parameter#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"1108":{"id":"/docs/glossary/parameter-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/parameter","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/parameter#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"1109":{"id":"/docs/glossary/parameter-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/parameter","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/parameter#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"1110":{"id":"/docs/glossary/parameter-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/parameter","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/parameter#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"1111":{"id":"/docs/glossary/parameter-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/parameter","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/parameter#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"1112":{"id":"/docs/glossary/parameter-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/parameter","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/parameter#heading-8","content":"References"},"1113":{"id":"/docs/glossary/parameter-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/parameter","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/parameter#Parameter","content":"A learnable numeric value stored in the model weights that training updates to fit data.\n\nParameter\nA learnable numeric value stored in the model weights that training updates to fit data.\nParameters are the persistent numbers in weight matrices and bias vectors that optimization nudges so forward passes produce better predictions.\nWhat It Is\nA parameter is any scalar or tensor element whose value is learned from data rather than fixed by hand. In transformers, most parameters live in linear projection weights, embedding tables, and layer-normalization scales.\nWhy It Matters\nParameter count drives memory footprint and training cost. When you read about fine-tuning or quantization, you are usually talking about how those stored weights are updated or compressed—not about activations, which are recomputed each forward pass.\nSimple Example\nA single attention projection might store a weight matrix W with shape (hidden, hidden). Every entry in W is a parameter; a gradient later tells each entry whether to increase or decrease.\nWhere It Appears\nCheckpoints list parameter tensors by name. Optimizer state (momentum, Adam moments) mirrors parameter shapes but is separate storage used only during training.\nCommon Confusions\nParameters are not activations: parameters persist in the checkpoint, while activations are temporary values flowing through the network for one input. Parameters are also not logits or softmax outputs—those are computed from parameters plus the current input.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nAfter softmax shows how predictions are scored, parameters are what training actually rewrites so those scores improve on real examples."},"1114":{"id":"/docs/glossary/parameter-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/parameter","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/parameter","content":"model parameters"},"1115":{"id":"/docs/glossary/parameter-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/parameter","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/parameter","content":"weights"},"1116":{"id":"/docs/glossary/parameter-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/parameter","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/parameter","content":"learnable weights"},"1117":{"id":"/docs/glossary/parameter-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/parameter","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/parameter","content":"token-to-probability-chain"},"1118":{"id":"/docs/glossary/parameter-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/parameter","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/parameter","content":"token to probability chain"},"1119":{"id":"/docs/glossary/parameter-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/parameter","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/parameter","content":"phase 2 probability chain"},"1120":{"id":"/docs/glossary/parameter-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/parameter","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/parameter","content":"foundations probability path"},"1121":{"id":"/docs/glossary/parameter-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/parameter","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/parameter","content":"foundations"},"1122":{"id":"/docs/glossary/parameter-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/parameter","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/parameter","content":"foundational concepts"},"1123":{"id":"/docs/glossary/parameter-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/parameter","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/parameter","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"1124":{"id":"/docs/glossary/parameter-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/parameter","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/parameter","content":"core vocabulary"},"1125":{"id":"/docs/glossary/parameter-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/parameter","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/parameter","content":"token-to-probability-chain"},"1126":{"id":"/docs/glossary/parameter-23","page_id":"/docs/glossary/parameter","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/parameter","content":"foundations"},"1127":{"id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","page_id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","type":"page","content":"Emergent Behavior","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior"},"1128":{"id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","content":"Qualitative capability jumps that appear only past certain model scale or training thresholds—distinct from smooth metric improvements tracked by scaling laws."},"1129":{"id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior#heading-0","content":"Emergent Behavior"},"1130":{"id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"1131":{"id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"1132":{"id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"1133":{"id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"1134":{"id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"1135":{"id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"1136":{"id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"1137":{"id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior#heading-8","content":"References"},"1138":{"id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior#Emergent Behavior","content":"Qualitative capability jumps that appear only past certain model scale or training thresholds—distinct from smooth metric improvements tracked by scaling laws.\n\nEmergent Behavior\nQualitative capability jumps that appear only past certain model scale or training thresholds—distinct from smooth metric improvements tracked by scaling laws.\nEmergent behavior names capabilities absent at smaller scale that appear reliably above a threshold—often debated against smooth metric improvements with scale.\nWhat It Is\nEmergent behavior (often called emergent abilities in papers) describes qualitative jumps: a benchmark accuracy curve is flat, then rises quickly once model size or training crosses a threshold. Researchers debate measurement definitions—some jumps shrink when metrics are rescaled—but the term still marks behaviors that were not predictable from small-model trends alone.\nWhy It Matters\nRoadmaps and safety reviews care about thresholds where models gain new skills. Scaling laws explain smooth loss trends; emergent behavior highlights tasks where capability seems discontinuous. Generalization and alignment still determine whether those skills help users safely in production.\nSimple Example\nA multiple-choice reasoning task may sit near chance for 8B models, then climb sharply at 70B while perplexity on web text improved smoothly across sizes—suggesting some skills are not visible from loss alone.\nWhere It Appears\nScaling and capability papers, benchmark suites with sharp scale thresholds, and product announcements about new model tiers. Link back to scaling law for smooth trends and generalization for whether skills transfer beyond the benchmark.\nCommon Confusions\nNot every benchmark improvement is emergent—many tasks scale gradually. Emergence is not magic; it can reflect metric nonlinearities or richer pretraining mixtures. It also does not replace alignment: a newly emergent skill can still be misused without policy controls.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nCheck whether the capability truly appeared abruptly on a well-defined metric or only after changing the prompt or grading rubric."},"1139":{"id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","content":"Emergent behavior"},"1140":{"id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","content":"emergent abilities"},"1141":{"id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","content":"capability emergence"},"1142":{"id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","content":"qualitative jumps"},"1143":{"id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","content":"foundations"},"1144":{"id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","content":"foundational concepts"},"1145":{"id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"1146":{"id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","content":"core vocabulary"},"1147":{"id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","content":"taxonomy"},"1148":{"id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","content":"glossary taxonomy"},"1149":{"id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","content":"atlas taxonomy"},"1150":{"id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","content":"taxonomy glossary"},"1151":{"id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior-23","page_id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","content":"cross-family taxonomy"},"1152":{"id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior-24","page_id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","content":"foundations"},"1153":{"id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior-25","page_id":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/emergent-behavior","content":"taxonomy"},"1154":{"id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts","page_id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts","type":"page","content":"Mixture of experts","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts"},"1155":{"id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts","content":"A sparse feed-forward layer that routes each token to a small subset of expert MLPs instead of one dense block."},"1156":{"id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts#heading-0","content":"Mixture of experts"},"1157":{"id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"1158":{"id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"1159":{"id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"1160":{"id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts#heading-4","content":"Common Confusions"},"1161":{"id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts#heading-5","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"1162":{"id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts#heading-6","content":"Tags"},"1163":{"id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts#heading-7","content":"References"},"1164":{"id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts#Mixture of experts","content":"A sparse feed-forward layer that routes each token to a small subset of expert MLPs instead of one dense block.\n\nMixture of experts\nA sparse feed-forward layer that routes each token to a small subset of expert MLPs instead of one dense block.\nA mixture-of-experts layer routes each token through a few specialist MLPs instead of one dense feed-forward block, trading sparse activation for extra capacity.\nWhat It Is\nA mixture-of-experts (MoE) layer replaces the single dense feed-forward network in a transformer block with many parallel expert MLPs plus a router. For each token position, a gating network scores every expert and sends the hidden vector to only the top-k experts—often one or two. Each chosen expert runs the usual expand–activate–project recipe; their outputs are weighted and summed back into one updated vector.\nWhy It Matters\nMoE increases total parameter count while keeping compute per token roughly flat, because only a few experts activate per step. That tradeoff matters when scaling language models: you can add capacity without multiplying FLOPs for every position. Capacity limits, load balancing, and routing noise also shape training stability, so recognizing MoE helps you read model cards that list expert counts and top-k routing.\nSimple Example\nSuppose a block has sixty-four expert MLPs but top-2 routing. A token vector enters the router, which picks the two highest-scoring experts—say experts 7 and 41. Each expert applies its own two-layer MLP; the router weights blend their outputs into one vector that continues through normalization and the residual add. The next token in the batch may activate a completely different pair.\nCommon Confusions\nMoE is not a model ensemble: ensembles combine separate full models at inference, while MoE keeps one shared stack and only sparsely activates internal experts. MoE is also not the same as a dense FFN—both sit after attention in the block, but dense FFN runs one MLP for every token whereas MoE selects a small subset. Finally, total expert parameters are not all used on every forward pass; active compute tracks top-k, not the full expert pool.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences"},"1165":{"id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts","content":"MoE"},"1166":{"id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts","content":"mixture-of-experts layer"},"1167":{"id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts","content":"sparse MoE"},"1168":{"id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts","content":"foundations"},"1169":{"id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts","content":"foundational concepts"},"1170":{"id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"1171":{"id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts","content":"core vocabulary"},"1172":{"id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/mixture-of-experts","content":"foundations"},"1173":{"id":"/docs/glossary/tensor","page_id":"/docs/glossary/tensor","type":"page","content":"Tensor","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/tensor"},"1174":{"id":"/docs/glossary/tensor-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/tensor","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/tensor","content":"A multi-dimensional array of numbers that carries activations, weights, or gradients through the network."},"1175":{"id":"/docs/glossary/tensor-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/tensor","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/tensor#heading-0","content":"Tensor"},"1176":{"id":"/docs/glossary/tensor-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/tensor","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/tensor#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"1177":{"id":"/docs/glossary/tensor-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/tensor","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/tensor#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"1178":{"id":"/docs/glossary/tensor-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/tensor","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/tensor#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"1179":{"id":"/docs/glossary/tensor-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/tensor","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/tensor#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"1180":{"id":"/docs/glossary/tensor-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/tensor","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/tensor#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"1181":{"id":"/docs/glossary/tensor-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/tensor","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/tensor#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"1182":{"id":"/docs/glossary/tensor-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/tensor","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/tensor#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"1183":{"id":"/docs/glossary/tensor-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/tensor","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/tensor#heading-8","content":"References"},"1184":{"id":"/docs/glossary/tensor-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/tensor","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/tensor#Tensor","content":"A multi-dimensional array of numbers that carries activations, weights, or gradients through the network.\n\nTensor\nA multi-dimensional array of numbers that carries activations, weights, or gradients through the network.\nA tensor is an n-dimensional array with a shape like batch × sequence × hidden; embeddings, activations, and logits are all tensors at different ranks.\nWhat It Is\nIn deep learning, a tensor generalizes vectors and matrices to any number of dimensions. Frameworks such as PyTorch and JAX store model state and activations as tensors and run operations (matmul, softmax, layer norm) that preserve or reshape those dimensions.\nWhy It Matters\nShape errors are among the most common debugging surprises: a logits tensor might be [batch, vocab] while hidden states are [batch, seq, hidden]. Naming tensors by role (embeddings, keys, values) keeps papers, code, and this reference aligned.\nSimple Example\nA minibatch of 4 sequences, each 128 tokens wide, with hidden size 768 is often written as a tensor of shape 4×128×768. The language-model head may reduce the last dimension to vocabulary size, yielding 4×128×50257 logits before softmax.\nWhere It Appears\nTensors flow through every layer: embedding lookups, attention scores, feed-forward activations, loss computation, and optimizer updates. GPU kernels and compilation stacks are built around batched tensor programs.\nCommon Confusions\nA tensor in ML is a numeric array, not the same as a tensor in general relativity. A single vector is a 1-D tensor; a matrix is 2-D. Scalars are 0-D tensors. Do not confuse tensor with parameter—parameters are tensors that get updated during training.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nOnce you are comfortable with tensor shapes, the next step in this chain is logits—the raw scores the model emits before softmax turns them into probabilities."},"1185":{"id":"/docs/glossary/tensor-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/tensor","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/tensor","content":"tensors"},"1186":{"id":"/docs/glossary/tensor-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/tensor","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/tensor","content":"multi-dimensional array"},"1187":{"id":"/docs/glossary/tensor-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/tensor","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/tensor","content":"token-to-probability-chain"},"1188":{"id":"/docs/glossary/tensor-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/tensor","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/tensor","content":"token to probability chain"},"1189":{"id":"/docs/glossary/tensor-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/tensor","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/tensor","content":"phase 2 probability chain"},"1190":{"id":"/docs/glossary/tensor-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/tensor","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/tensor","content":"foundations probability path"},"1191":{"id":"/docs/glossary/tensor-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/tensor","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/tensor","content":"foundations"},"1192":{"id":"/docs/glossary/tensor-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/tensor","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/tensor","content":"foundational concepts"},"1193":{"id":"/docs/glossary/tensor-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/tensor","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/tensor","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"1194":{"id":"/docs/glossary/tensor-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/tensor","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/tensor","content":"core vocabulary"},"1195":{"id":"/docs/glossary/tensor-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/tensor","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/tensor","content":"token-to-probability-chain"},"1196":{"id":"/docs/glossary/tensor-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/tensor","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/tensor","content":"foundations"},"1197":{"id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection","page_id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection","type":"page","content":"Residual connection","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection"},"1198":{"id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection","content":"Skip paths that add each sublayer's output back onto the running hidden stream so deep transformer stacks stay trainable."},"1199":{"id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection#heading-0","content":"Residual connection"},"1200":{"id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"1201":{"id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"1202":{"id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"1203":{"id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection#heading-4","content":"Common Confusions"},"1204":{"id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection#heading-5","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"1205":{"id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection#heading-6","content":"Tags"},"1206":{"id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection","type":"heading","tags":["foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection#heading-7","content":"References"},"1207":{"id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection#Residual connection","content":"Skip paths that add each sublayer's output back onto the running hidden stream so deep transformer stacks stay trainable.\n\nResidual connection\nSkip paths that add each sublayer's output back onto the running hidden stream so deep transformer stacks stay trainable.\nResidual connections add each sublayer's output back onto the running hidden stream, giving gradients a skip highway through depth and pairing with pre-norm or post-norm placement around attention and feed-forward blocks.\nWhat It Is\nA residual connection—also called a skip connection or residual add—carries the input of a sublayer forward and adds it to that sublayer's output. In transformers, the same hidden vector stream passes through attention, feed-forward layers, and normalization while residuals preserve a direct path from earlier layers. Each block typically applies two residual adds: one around attention and one around the feed-forward network.\nWhy It Matters\nDeep stacks would be hard to train if every layer had to learn the full transformation from scratch. Residuals let each sublayer learn a small update on top of what already flows through the stream, which keeps gradients from vanishing on the skip highway during backpropagation. Placement relative to normalization also shapes training: pre-norm applies layer norm before each sublayer and adds the result back onto the stream afterward, while post-norm normalizes after the add. Most modern decoder language models use pre-norm because it tends to stabilize optimization at large depth.\nSimple Example\nImagine one token vector entering a block. Pre-norm attention reads a normalized copy of the stream, mixes context from other positions, and writes its output back with a residual add so the original stream is never fully replaced. The feed-forward sublayer repeats the pattern: normalize, apply the dense MLP, then add onto the same residual stream before the next block receives the vector.\nCommon Confusions\nA residual add is not the same as normalization: residuals preserve and sum streams, while norm layers rescale activations. The residual stream is also not a second hidden size—it is the main width that every sublayer reads and writes. Finally, skip connections here are inside one model stack, not shortcuts between separate ensemble members.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences"},"1208":{"id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection","content":"skip connection"},"1209":{"id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection","content":"residual stream"},"1210":{"id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection","content":"residual add"},"1211":{"id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection","content":"foundations"},"1212":{"id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection","content":"foundational concepts"},"1213":{"id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"1214":{"id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection","content":"core vocabulary"},"1215":{"id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection","tags":["foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/residual-connection","content":"foundations"},"1216":{"id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation","page_id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation","type":"page","content":"Autoregressive Generation","tags":["foundations","taxonomy","attention"],"url":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation"},"1217":{"id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation","tags":["foundations","taxonomy","attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation","content":"A generation paradigm that produces outputs one discrete step at a time, each step conditioned on everything generated so far."},"1218":{"id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy","attention"],"url":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation#heading-0","content":"Autoregressive Generation"},"1219":{"id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy","attention"],"url":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"1220":{"id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy","attention"],"url":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"1221":{"id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy","attention"],"url":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"1222":{"id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy","attention"],"url":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"1223":{"id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy","attention"],"url":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"1224":{"id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy","attention"],"url":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"1225":{"id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy","attention"],"url":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"1226":{"id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy","attention"],"url":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation#heading-8","content":"References"},"1227":{"id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation","tags":["foundations","taxonomy","attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation#Autoregressive Generation","content":"A generation paradigm that produces outputs one discrete step at a time, each step conditioned on everything generated so far.\n\nAutoregressive Generation\nA generation paradigm that produces outputs one discrete step at a time, each step conditioned on everything generated so far.\nAutoregressive generation samples or selects one output unit—usually the next token—then feeds that choice back as context, with each step running through embeddings, logits, and softmax before the decoder advances.\nWhat It Is\nAt inference, the model holds a growing prefix of tokens (or other discrete units). The decoder computes logits over the vocabulary, softmax turns them into probabilities, and the chosen unit is appended. KV caches store past keys and values so earlier positions are not recomputed. Encoder–decoder setups still autoregress on the decoder side while reading fixed encoder memory.\nWhy It Matters\nAutoregressive generation is the dominant text and code paradigm and the output mode most decoder and encoder–decoder pages reference. It connects the token chain—token IDs, embeddings, logits, softmax—to architecture choices such as causal attention, KV-cache sizing, and grouped-query attention for efficient decoding.\nSimple Example\nGiven the prefix \"The capital of France is\", the model outputs logits for the next token, softmax peaks on \"Paris\", that token is appended, and the process repeats until an end-of-sequence token or length limit.\nWhere It Appears\nGPT-style decoder-only models, translation decoders in encoder–decoder transformers, speech token decoders, and some multimodal models that emit discrete visual tokens all use autoregressive steps. Denoising generation covers the other major family that iterates in continuous latent space instead of discrete token steps.\nCommon Confusions\nAutoregressive generation is not the same as any decoder block—decoders are architecture components, while autoregressive describes the step-by-step sampling loop. It is also not identical to teacher-forced training, where ground-truth prefixes are fed during optimization even though inference is autoregressive. Diffusion sampling loops over noise timesteps but is not token-autoregressive unless the model emits discrete tokens each step.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nFollow one step: embedding lookup → decoder forward → logits → softmax → append token. Repeat until done."},"1228":{"id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation","tags":["foundations","taxonomy","attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation","content":"Autoregressive generation"},"1229":{"id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation","tags":["foundations","taxonomy","attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation","content":"autoregressive decoding"},"1230":{"id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation","tags":["foundations","taxonomy","attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation","content":"next-token generation"},"1231":{"id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation","tags":["foundations","taxonomy","attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation","content":"AR generation"},"1232":{"id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation","tags":["foundations","taxonomy","attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation","content":"foundations"},"1233":{"id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation","tags":["foundations","taxonomy","attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation","content":"foundational concepts"},"1234":{"id":"/docs/glossary/autoregressive-generation