l":"/docs/glossary/latent-space#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"1251":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/latent-space#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"1252":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/latent-space#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"1253":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/latent-space#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"1254":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/latent-space#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"1255":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/latent-space#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"1256":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/latent-space#heading-8","content":"References"},"1257":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent-space#Latent Space","content":"The coordinate system in which latent codes live, where distance and direction correspond to semantic or structural variation in the data.\n\nLatent Space\nThe coordinate system in which latent codes live, where distance and direction correspond to semantic or structural variation in the data.\nLatent space is the structured vector manifold where latents live; encoders map inputs into it and decoders or denoisers map points back to outputs.\nWhat It Is\nLatent space organizes all latent codes for a model family: VAE priors, diffusion noise schedules viewed across timesteps, or shared multimodal alignment spaces. Geometry matters—nearby points should correspond to similar decoded outputs after the decoder or denoising steps.\nWhy It Matters\nUnderstanding latent space separates representation learning from generation mechanics. It explains why interpolation works, why regularization targets KL terms, and why encoders and denoising generators are paired in diffusion and autoencoder stacks.\nSimple Example\nTwo face latents averaged in latent space decode to a blended face after the decoder runs. Moving along one principal direction might change smile intensity if the space disentangles factors—quality depends on training, not on the word latent alone.\nWhere It Appears\nLatent space is central to VAEs, latent diffusion, and multimodal encoders that align image and text latents. Forward links in this foundation chain point to encoders that populate the space and denoising generation that walks through it during sampling.\nCommon Confusions\nLatent space is not the tokenizer vocabulary or embedding table—that is discrete input indexing. It is also not parameter space (weights); latents are activations or stochastic codes during inference. A single latent vector is a point in latent space, not the space itself.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nWhen docs say \"move in latent space,\" ask which encoder produced the coordinates and which decoder or denoiser reads them back out."},"1258":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","content":"latent manifold"},"1259":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","content":"compressed representation space"},"1260":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","content":"latent representation space"},"1261":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","content":"foundations"},"1262":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","content":"foundational concepts"},"1263":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"1264":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","content":"core vocabulary"},"1265":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","content":"taxonomy"},"1266":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","content":"glossary taxonomy"},"1267":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","content":"atlas taxonomy"},"1268":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","content":"taxonomy glossary"},"1269":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","content":"cross-family taxonomy"},"1270":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space-23","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","content":"foundations"},"1271":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space-24","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent-space","content":"taxonomy"},"1272":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent","type":"page","content":"Latent","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/latent"},"1273":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent","content":"A compressed internal code that summarizes input structure for reconstruction, generation, or downstream tasks."},"1274":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/latent#heading-0","content":"Latent"},"1275":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/latent#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"1276":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/latent#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"1277":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/latent#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"1278":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/latent#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"1279":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/latent#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"1280":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/latent#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"1281":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/latent#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"1282":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/latent#heading-8","content":"References"},"1283":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent#Latent","content":"A compressed internal code that summarizes input structure for reconstruction, generation, or downstream tasks.\n\nLatent\nA compressed internal code that summarizes input structure for reconstruction, generation, or downstream tasks.\nA latent is an internal variable—trained code, diffusion state, or compressed hidden vector—that carries information in fewer degrees of freedom than the raw input.\nWhat It Is\nLatents appear after encoders or inside generative objectives: VAE means, diffusion x_t states at a timestep, or bottleneck vectors in autoencoders. They are representations chosen for efficiency or controllability, not raw patches or tokenizer outputs.\nWhy It Matters\nSeparating latent from patch and from the full latent space helps you compare diffusion, VAE, and autoregressive stacks. It also clarifies which tensors are safe to manipulate at inference—interpolating latents, swapping style codes, or conditioning denoisers.\nSimple Example\nAn image autoencoder maps a photo to a 512-dimensional latent vector, then a decoder reconstructs pixels from that vector. The latent is the bottleneck code; the decoder readout is not itself the latent.\nWhere It Appears\nLatents show up in variational and diffusion training, contrastive encoders, and multimodal alignment when one modality is projected into another's space. Latent space names the geometry those codes inhabit together.\nCommon Confusions\nLatent versus representation: every latent is a representation, but not every hidden state is called a latent—authors usually reserve the term for compressed or stochastic codes. Latent versus embedding: embeddings often mean discrete lookup tables at the input; latents are typically continuous codes deeper in the stack. Latent is not the same as a noise sample in diffusion unless the text explicitly refers to the noised state as the working variable.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nIf the tensor is the deliberate bottleneck or generative state variable, call it a latent; if it is any hidden activation, use representation."},"1284":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent","content":"latent code"},"1285":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent","content":"latent variable"},"1286":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent","content":"latent vector"},"1287":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent","content":"foundations"},"1288":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent","content":"foundational concepts"},"1289":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"1290":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent","content":"core vocabulary"},"1291":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent","content":"taxonomy"},"1292":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent","content":"glossary taxonomy"},"1293":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent","content":"atlas taxonomy"},"1294":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent","content":"taxonomy glossary"},"1295":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent","content":"cross-family taxonomy"},"1296":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-23","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent","content":"foundations"},"1297":{"id":"/docs/glossary/latent-24","page_id":"/docs/glossary/latent","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/latent","content":"taxonomy"},"1298":{"id":"/docs/glossary/temperature","page_id":"/docs/glossary/temperature","type":"page","content":"Temperature","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/temperature"},"1299":{"id":"/docs/glossary/temperature-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/temperature","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/temperature","content":"A positive scaling factor applied to logits before softmax to make the next-token distribution sharper or flatter."},"1300":{"id":"/docs/glossary/temperature-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/temperature","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/temperature#heading-0","content":"Temperature"},"1301":{"id":"/docs/glossary/temperature-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/temperature","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/temperature#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"1302":{"id":"/docs/glossary/temperature-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/temperature","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/temperature#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"1303":{"id":"/docs/glossary/temperature-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/temperature","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/temperature#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"1304":{"id":"/docs/glossary/temperature-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/temperature","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/temperature#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"1305":{"id":"/docs/glossary/temperature-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/temperature","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/temperature#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"1306":{"id":"/docs/glossary/temperature-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/temperature","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/temperature#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"1307":{"id":"/docs/glossary/temperature-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/temperature","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/temperature#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"1308":{"id":"/docs/glossary/temperature-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/temperature","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/temperature#heading-8","content":"References"},"1309":{"id":"/docs/glossary/temperature-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/temperature","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/temperature#Temperature","content":"A positive scaling factor applied to logits before softmax to make the next-token distribution sharper or flatter.\n\nTemperature\nA positive scaling factor applied to logits before softmax to make the next-token distribution sharper or flatter.\nTemperature divides logits by T before softmax: T below 1 sharpens the distribution, T above 1 flattens it, and T equal to 1 leaves the model's raw scores unchanged.\nWhat It Is\nTemperature is a positive scalar used at inference (and sometimes in analysis) as softmax(z / T). It does not change model weights—it only rescales logits immediately before normalization.\nWhy It Matters\nCreative writing APIs often raise temperature for diverse outputs; factual or code assistants lower it for deterministic answers. Because temperature acts on logits before softmax, it directly controls how sharply probabilities concentrate on top tokens.\nSimple Example\nWith logits [2, 1, 0], temperature 0.5 divides by a smaller T, exaggerating differences so softmax favors index 0 even more. Temperature 2.0 dampens gaps so the three probabilities move closer together.\nWhere It Appears\nHosted chat APIs expose a temperature parameter on completion calls. Local runtimes apply temperature scaling divides logits before softmax inside sampling kernels. Distinctive chain phrase: temperature scaling divides logits before softmax at sample time.\nCommon Confusions\nTemperature is not the same as top-p or top-k filtering—those truncate or renormalize after probabilities exist. Setting temperature to zero is handled as a limit toward argmax in many libraries, not as literal division by zero.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nRemember: lower temperature → sharper softmax → more repetitive outputs; higher temperature → flatter softmax → more surprise."},"1310":{"id":"/docs/glossary/temperature-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/temperature","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/temperature","content":"sampling temperature"},"1311":{"id":"/docs/glossary/temperature-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/temperature","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/temperature","content":"softmax temperature"},"1312":{"id":"/docs/glossary/temperature-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/temperature","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/temperature","content":"token-to-probability-chain"},"1313":{"id":"/docs/glossary/temperature-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/temperature","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/temperature","content":"token to probability chain"},"1314":{"id":"/docs/glossary/temperature-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/temperature","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/temperature","content":"phase 2 probability chain"},"1315":{"id":"/docs/glossary/temperature-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/temperature","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/temperature","content":"foundations probability path"},"1316":{"id":"/docs/glossary/temperature-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/temperature","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/temperature","content":"foundations"},"1317":{"id":"/docs/glossary/temperature-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/temperature","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/temperature","content":"foundational concepts"},"1318":{"id":"/docs/glossary/temperature-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/temperature","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/temperature","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"1319":{"id":"/docs/glossary/temperature-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/temperature","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/temperature","content":"core vocabulary"},"1320":{"id":"/docs/glossary/temperature-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/temperature","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/temperature","content":"token-to-probability-chain"},"1321":{"id":"/docs/glossary/temperature-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/temperature","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/temperature","content":"foundations"},"1322":{"id":"/docs/glossary/vector","page_id":"/docs/glossary/vector","type":"page","content":"Vector","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/vector"},"1323":{"id":"/docs/glossary/vector-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/vector","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/vector","content":"An ordered list of numbers that represents a point or direction in continuous space—embeddings and activations are vectors at different stages of the model."},"1324":{"id":"/docs/glossary/vector-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/vector","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/vector#heading-0","content":"Vector"},"1325":{"id":"/docs/glossary/vector-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/vector","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/vector#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"1326":{"id":"/docs/glossary/vector-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/vector","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/vector#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"1327":{"id":"/docs/glossary/vector-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/vector","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/vector#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"1328":{"id":"/docs/glossary/vector-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/vector","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/vector#heading-4","content":"Common Confusions"},"1329":{"id":"/docs/glossary/vector-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/vector","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/vector#heading-5","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"1330":{"id":"/docs/glossary/vector-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/vector","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/vector#heading-6","content":"Tags"},"1331":{"id":"/docs/glossary/vector-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/vector","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/vector#heading-7","content":"References"},"1332":{"id":"/docs/glossary/vector-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/vector","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/vector#Vector","content":"An ordered list of numbers that represents a point or direction in continuous space—embeddings and activations are vectors at different stages of the model.\n\nVector\nAn ordered list of numbers that represents a point or direction in continuous space—embeddings and activations are vectors at different stages of the model.\nA vector is an ordered list of numbers; token embeddings and per-position hidden states are vectors that later stack into tensors as they move through the model.\nWhat It Is\nA vector is a fixed-length sequence of real numbers. In language models, token embeddings are vectors of model width, and attention layers read and write vectors at every position along the sequence.\nWhy It Matters\nPapers and code often say \"vector\" when they mean a 1-D tensor: one row from an embedding table, a query vector, or a hidden state. Knowing that vectors are the building blocks inside tensors helps you follow shape notation from embeddings through attention. For shape conventions, broadcasting, and framework dtypes, see the tensor and embedding glossary entries.\nSimple Example\nA 768-dimensional embedding for one token is a vector of length 768. Stacking many positions produces a matrix or higher-rank tensor, but each row is still a vector in hidden space.\nCommon Confusions\nA vector is not the same as a sparse one-hot encoding: learned embeddings are dense vectors with values in every dimension. \"Dense vector\" usually contrasts with sparse bag-of-words features, not with tensors in general.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences"},"1333":{"id":"/docs/glossary/vector-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/vector","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/vector","content":"vector"},"1334":{"id":"/docs/glossary/vector-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/vector","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/vector","content":"vectors"},"1335":{"id":"/docs/glossary/vector-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/vector","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/vector","content":"dense vector"},"1336":{"id":"/docs/glossary/vector-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/vector","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/vector","content":"token-to-probability-chain"},"1337":{"id":"/docs/glossary/vector-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/vector","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/vector","content":"token to probability chain"},"1338":{"id":"/docs/glossary/vector-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/vector","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/vector","content":"phase 2 probability chain"},"1339":{"id":"/docs/glossary/vector-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/vector","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/vector","content":"foundations probability path"},"1340":{"id":"/docs/glossary/vector-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/vector","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/vector","content":"foundations"},"1341":{"id":"/docs/glossary/vector-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/vector","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/vector","content":"foundational concepts"},"1342":{"id":"/docs/glossary/vector-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/vector","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/vector","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"1343":{"id":"/docs/glossary/vector-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/vector","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/vector","content":"core vocabulary"},"1344":{"id":"/docs/glossary/vector-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/vector","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/vector","content":"token-to-probability-chain"},"1345":{"id":"/docs/glossary/vector-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/vector","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/vector","content":"foundations"},"1346":{"id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","page_id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","type":"page","content":"Encoder-Decoder","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder"},"1347":{"id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","content":"An architecture that compresses input into representations with an encoder, then generates outputs with a decoder—often via cross-attention between the two stacks."},"1348":{"id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder#heading-0","content":"Encoder-Decoder"},"1349":{"id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"1350":{"id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"1351":{"id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"1352":{"id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"1353":{"id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"1354":{"id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"1355":{"id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"1356":{"id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","type":"heading","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"url":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder#heading-8","content":"References"},"1357":{"id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder#Encoder-Decoder","content":"An architecture that compresses input into representations with an encoder, then generates outputs with a decoder—often via cross-attention between the two stacks.\n\nEncoder-Decoder\nAn architecture that compresses input into representations with an encoder, then generates outputs with a decoder—often via cross-attention between the two stacks.\nEncoder–decoder models pair an input-side encoder with an output-side decoder that conditions on encoder memory while generating outputs step by step.\nWhat It Is\nClassic transformer translation uses a bidirectional encoder over the source and a causal decoder over the target with cross-attention into encoder states. Variants appear in speech (encoder over audio, decoder over text), multimodal captioning, and T5-style text-to-text frameworks where both sides are token sequences.\nWhy It Matters\nThe split explains capacity allocation: encoders can see the full input while decoders remain causal for generation. It also motivates autoregressive generation as the decoder output paradigm and contrasts with decoder-only models that fold encoding and decoding into one causal stack.\nSimple Example\nEnglish→French translation encodes the English sentence into memory vectors, then the decoder generates French tokens while attending to those vectors at each step. The encoder never emits French tokens; the decoder never re-reads raw English after encoding finishes.\nWhere It Appears\nEncoder–decoder transformers underpin machine translation, summarization, and many speech and vision-language systems. Forward links in this chain point to autoregressive generation for how decoders emit outputs and to transformer as the dominant block architecture inside both stacks.\nCommon Confusions\nEncoder–decoder is an architecture pattern, not a training objective—you still need a loss and data pipeline. It is also distinct from encoder-only BERT models (no decoder) and decoder-only GPT models (no separate encoder). T5 is encoder–decoder even when input and output are both text.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nIf one stack reads the full input and another generates outputs with cross-attention between them, you are looking at encoder–decoder—not decoder-only."},"1358":{"id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","content":"seq2seq"},"1359":{"id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","content":"encoder decoder"},"1360":{"id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","content":"encoder-decoder architecture"},"1361":{"id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","content":"foundations"},"1362":{"id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","content":"foundational concepts"},"1363":{"id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"1364":{"id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","content":"core vocabulary"},"1365":{"id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","content":"taxonomy"},"1366":{"id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","content":"glossary taxonomy"},"1367":{"id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","content":"atlas taxonomy"},"1368":{"id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","content":"taxonomy glossary"},"1369":{"id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","content":"cross-family taxonomy"},"1370":{"id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder-23","page_id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","content":"foundations"},"1371":{"id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder-24","page_id":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","tags":["foundations","taxonomy"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/encoder-decoder","content":"taxonomy"},"1372":{"id":"/docs/glossary/logit","page_id":"/docs/glossary/logit","type":"page","content":"Logit","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/logit"},"1373":{"id":"/docs/glossary/logit-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/logit","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/logit","content":"A raw, unnormalized score for each vocabulary item before softmax turns scores into probabilities."},"1374":{"id":"/docs/glossary/logit-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/logit","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/logit#heading-0","content":"Logit"},"1375":{"id":"/docs/glossary/logit-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/logit","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/logit#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"1376":{"id":"/docs/glossary/logit-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/logit","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/logit#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"1377":{"id":"/docs/glossary/logit-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/logit","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/logit#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"1378":{"id":"/docs/glossary/logit-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/logit","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/logit#heading-4","content":"Where It Appears"},"1379":{"id":"/docs/glossary/logit-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/logit","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/logit#heading-5","content":"Common Confusions"},"1380":{"id":"/docs/glossary/logit-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/logit","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/logit#heading-6","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"1381":{"id":"/docs/glossary/logit-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/logit","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/logit#heading-7","content":"Tags"},"1382":{"id":"/docs/glossary/logit-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/logit","type":"heading","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"url":"/docs/glossary/logit#heading-8","content":"References"},"1383":{"id":"/docs/glossary/logit-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/logit","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/logit#Logit","content":"A raw, unnormalized score for each vocabulary item before softmax turns scores into probabilities.\n\nLogit\nA raw, unnormalized score for each vocabulary item before softmax turns scores into probabilities.\nLogits are the pre-softmax scores the vocabulary head assigns—one per token—that softmax converts into next-token probabilities.\nWhat It Is\nA logit is a real-valued score assigned to a single vocabulary choice at a position, typically produced by a weight matrix applied to hidden states. The full vector of logits has length equal to vocabulary size; no entry is guaranteed to lie between 0 and 1 until softmax runs.\nWhy It Matters\nSampling, loss functions, and interpretability all refer to logits or to probabilities derived from them. Temperature scaling divides logits before softmax; ranking tokens by logit alone often matches ranking by probability when softmax is monotonic.\nSimple Example\nSuppose the model emits three logits for candidate next tokens. Softmax will map those three numbers to values that sum to 1; the largest logit usually becomes the largest probability, but the scale of logits only matters relative to each other.\nWhere It Appears\nDecoder-only language models apply an output projection (often tied to the input embedding matrix) to hidden states at each position, yielding a logits tensor shaped like batch × sequence × vocabulary. Training code may keep logits in float32 even when activations use lower precision.\nCommon Confusions\nLogits are not probabilities: they can be negative, greater than one, and need not sum to 1. Logits are also not the same as log-probabilities unless you explicitly take a log of normalized probabilities. The plural logits refers to the whole score vector.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nThink pre-softmax score: logits are the numbers softmax eats. The next page in this chain shows exactly how that normalization works."},"1384":{"id":"/docs/glossary/logit-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/logit","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/logit","content":"logits"},"1385":{"id":"/docs/glossary/logit-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/logit","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/logit","content":"raw score"},"1386":{"id":"/docs/glossary/logit-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/logit","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/logit","content":"pre-softmax score"},"1387":{"id":"/docs/glossary/logit-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/logit","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/logit","content":"token-to-probability-chain"},"1388":{"id":"/docs/glossary/logit-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/logit","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/logit","content":"token to probability chain"},"1389":{"id":"/docs/glossary/logit-16","page_id":"/docs/glossary/logit","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/logit","content":"phase 2 probability chain"},"1390":{"id":"/docs/glossary/logit-17","page_id":"/docs/glossary/logit","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/logit","content":"foundations probability path"},"1391":{"id":"/docs/glossary/logit-18","page_id":"/docs/glossary/logit","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/logit","content":"foundations"},"1392":{"id":"/docs/glossary/logit-19","page_id":"/docs/glossary/logit","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/logit","content":"foundational concepts"},"1393":{"id":"/docs/glossary/logit-20","page_id":"/docs/glossary/logit","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/logit","content":"phase 2 foundations"},"1394":{"id":"/docs/glossary/logit-21","page_id":"/docs/glossary/logit","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/logit","content":"core vocabulary"},"1395":{"id":"/docs/glossary/logit-22","page_id":"/docs/glossary/logit","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/logit","content":"token-to-probability-chain"},"1396":{"id":"/docs/glossary/logit-23","page_id":"/docs/glossary/logit","tags":["token-to-probability-chain","foundations"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/logit","content":"foundations"},"1397":{"id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model","page_id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model","type":"page","content":"Multimodal Model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"url":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model"},"1398":{"id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model-0","page_id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model","content":"A model family that accepts or produces more than one data modality, such as text paired with images or audio."},"1399":{"id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model-1","page_id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"url":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model#heading-0","content":"Multimodal Model"},"1400":{"id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model-2","page_id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"url":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"1401":{"id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model-3","page_id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"url":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"1402":{"id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model-4","page_id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"url":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model#heading-3","content":"Simple Example"},"1403":{"id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model-5","page_id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"url":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model#heading-4","content":"Common Confusions"},"1404":{"id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model-6","page_id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"url":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model#heading-5","content":"Related Concepts And Modules"},"1405":{"id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model-7","page_id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"url":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model#heading-6","content":"Tags"},"1406":{"id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model-8","page_id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model","type":"heading","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"url":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model#heading-7","content":"References"},"1407":{"id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model-9","page_id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model#Multimodal Model","content":"A model family that accepts or produces more than one data modality, such as text paired with images or audio.\n\nMultimodal Model\nA model family that accepts or produces more than one data modality, such as text paired with images or audio.\nMultimodal models coordinate two or more data channels—often text with images or audio—through shared encoders, cross-attention, or alignment projections so one network can reason across modalities.\nWhat It Is\nA multimodal model ingests or emits two or more modalities—text tokens, image patches, audio frames, video clips, or other channels—and learns shared representations that let those signals interact. Fusion can happen early through a joint encoder, late through cross-attention between modality-specific towers, or through adapters that project one modality into another's embedding space. The family name covers vision-language chat models, speech-to-text stacks, and image captioning systems that share the same high-level pattern: multiple input or output channels coordinated by one trained network.\nWhy It Matters\nMultimodal models sit beside unimodal language or vision checkpoints as a distinct architecture family because product behavior depends on which channels the weights actually see. Knowing the family separates true cross-modal fusion from chat UIs that route images through a separate tool. The architecture page groups multimodal models with other families; this page is the dedicated reference for models that align more than one modality through shared representations.\nSimple Example\nA vision-language assistant tokenizes a user question as text, encodes an uploaded photo into patch embeddings, runs both through a transformer with cross-attention so text queries attend to image patches, then autoregressively decodes an answer in text tokens.\nCommon Confusions\nMultimodal model names a family defined by multiple modalities, not any single product or checkpoint size. Modality names the raw channel type; representation names the internal vectors after encoding; patch names a common image tokenization unit. A text-only transformer is not multimodal even when wrapped in a product that calls external APIs for images.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences"},"1408":{"id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model-10","page_id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model","content":"multimodal models"},"1409":{"id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model-11","page_id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model","content":"multimodal architecture"},"1410":{"id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model-12","page_id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model","content":"multi-modal model"},"1411":{"id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model-13","page_id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model","content":"taxonomy"},"1412":{"id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model-14","page_id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model","tags":["taxonomy","model-family"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model","content":"glossary taxonomy"},"1413":{"id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model-15","page_id":"/docs/glossary/multimodal-model