ention"},"1451":{"id":"/docs/modules/attention-2","page_id":"/docs/modules/attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/attention#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"1452":{"id":"/docs/modules/attention-3","page_id":"/docs/modules/attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/attention#heading-2","content":"Why It Matters"},"1453":{"id":"/docs/modules/attention-4","page_id":"/docs/modules/attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/attention#heading-3","content":"Attention Variants"},"1454":{"id":"/docs/modules/attention-5","page_id":"/docs/modules/attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/attention#heading-4","content":"Related"},"1455":{"id":"/docs/modules/attention-6","page_id":"/docs/modules/attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/attention#heading-5","content":"Tags"},"1456":{"id":"/docs/modules/attention-7","page_id":"/docs/modules/attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/attention#heading-6","content":"References"},"1457":{"id":"/docs/modules/attention-8","page_id":"/docs/modules/attention","tags":["attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/attention#Attention","content":"How transformer blocks mix information across token positions using query, key, and value projections.\n\nAttention\nHow transformer blocks mix information across token positions using query, key, and value projections.\nA sequence model must decide which earlier tokens matter for each position without hard-coding fixed windows or hand-built alignment rules; attention scores how much each position should read from every other position and blends value vectors according to those scores so context flows dynamically along the sequence.\nWhat It Is\nAttention is the core mixing mechanism in transformer blocks. Each position projects hidden states into queries, keys, and values, compares queries to keys to form weights, and sums value vectors to produce an updated representation.\nWhy It Matters\nWithout attention, deep stacks of feed-forward layers could not route information across arbitrary distances in one step. Head-sharing variants trade memory and bandwidth against how many distinct query and key-value heads you keep at inference time.\nAttention Variants\nTransformer blocks implement attention through parallel heads. Multi-head attention keeps independent key-value heads per query head; multi-query attention shares one KV head across all queries; grouped-query attention shares KV heads within groups while keeping more query diversity than multi-query attention.\nRelated\nTags\nReferences"},"1458":{"id":"/docs/modules/attention-9","page_id":"/docs/modules/attention","tags":["attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/attention","content":"attention"},"1459":{"id":"/docs/modules/attention-10","page_id":"/docs/modules/attention","tags":["attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/attention","content":"self-attention"},"1460":{"id":"/docs/modules/attention-11","page_id":"/docs/modules/attention","tags":["attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/attention","content":"attention mechanism"},"1461":{"id":"/docs/modules/attention-12","page_id":"/docs/modules/attention","tags":["attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/attention","content":"attention"},"1462":{"id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention","page_id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention","type":"page","content":"Sparse Attention","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention"},"1463":{"id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention-0","page_id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention","tags":["attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention","content":"An attention variant that computes scores only for a subset of token pairs instead of every query-key combination."},"1464":{"id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention-1","page_id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention#heading-0","content":"Sparse Attention"},"1465":{"id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention-2","page_id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"1466":{"id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention-3","page_id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention#heading-2","content":"What It Optimizes"},"1467":{"id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention-4","page_id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention#heading-3","content":"Practical Benefit"},"1468":{"id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention-5","page_id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention#heading-4","content":"How It Works"},"1469":{"id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention-6","page_id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention#heading-5","content":"Math Or Compute Schema"},"1470":{"id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention-7","page_id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention#heading-6","content":"Compared To Nearby Modules"},"1471":{"id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention-8","page_id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention#heading-7","content":"Example Architectures"},"1472":{"id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention-9","page_id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention#heading-8","content":"Limitations And Tradeoffs"},"1473":{"id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention-10","page_id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention#heading-9","content":"Why It Still Matters"},"1474":{"id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention-11","page_id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention#heading-10","content":"Related"},"1475":{"id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention-12","page_id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention#heading-11","content":"Tags"},"1476":{"id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention-13","page_id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention#heading-12","content":"References"},"1477":{"id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention-14","page_id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention","tags":["attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention#Sparse Attention","content":"An attention variant that computes scores only for a subset of token pairs instead of every query-key combination.\n\nSparse Attention\nAn attention variant that computes scores only for a subset of token pairs instead of every query-key combination.\nDense attention scores every query against every key, so compute and memory grow with the square of sequence length; sparse attention applies a mask or pattern that skips most token pairs and computes attention only where the pattern allows, trading full connectivity for lower cost on long contexts.\nWhat It Is\nSparse attention is an attention variant that restricts which query-key pairs participate in the softmax. Instead of a full n-by-n attention matrix, only entries allowed by a sparsity pattern receive non-zero weight.\nWhat It Optimizes\nSparse attention targets attention compute, memory bandwidth for score materialization, and the cost of serving long sequences when dense all-pairs attention would dominate runtime.\nPractical Benefit\nTeams adopt sparse attention when they need long-context modeling but cannot afford dense quadratic attention. Skipping disallowed pairs reduces multiply-accumulate work and the memory traffic needed to form and store full attention maps.\nHow It Works\nEach query position attends only to keys permitted by a sparsity mask or fixed pattern. Disallowed pairs are zeroed before softmax normalization, so the model spends compute on selected connections rather than the full token grid.\nMath Or Compute Schema\nWith sequence length n and sparsity mask M, sparse attention applies M to the score matrix before softmax. The formulas below contrast dense multi-head attention against masked sparse attention that limits which pairs receive weight.\nCompared To Nearby Modules\nCompared with multi-head attention, sparse attention skips most token pairs rather than scoring all of them. Multi-query and grouped-query attention remain dense over allowed positions but reduce KV head count; sparse attention changes which positions connect at all.\nExample Architectures\nSparse attention appears in long-context decoder models that combine local windows, block patterns, or learned sparsity with standard projection layers.\nLimitations And Tradeoffs\nRestricting connectivity can miss long-range dependencies that dense attention would capture. Pattern choice and mask quality strongly affect what information flows across the sequence.\nWhy It Still Matters\nAs sequence lengths grow, quadratic attention cost motivates sparsity patterns that preserve useful signal while avoiding a full n-by-n score matrix on every layer.\nRelated\nTags\nReferences\nDense multi-head attention versus sparse attention pair selection\nToggle MHA and sparse attention to compare all-pairs scoring against mask-limited pair selection on one canvas\nHow sparse attention compares with nearby attention variants"},"1478":{"id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention-15","page_id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention","tags":["attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention","content":"sparse attention"},"1479":{"id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention-16","page_id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention","tags":["attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention","content":"Sparse attention"},"1480":{"id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention-17","page_id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention","tags":["attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention","content":"attention"},"1481":{"id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention-18","page_id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention","tags":["attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention","content":"attention mechanism"},"1482":{"id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention-19","page_id":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention","tags":["attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/sparse-attention","content":"attention"},"1483":{"id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention","page_id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention","type":"page","content":"Linear Attention","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/linear-attention"},"1484":{"id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention-0","page_id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention","tags":["attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/linear-attention","content":"An attention variant that replaces explicit softmax dot-product attention with kernel or feature-map formulations that scale near-linearly with sequence length."},"1485":{"id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention-1","page_id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/linear-attention#heading-0","content":"Linear Attention"},"1486":{"id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention-2","page_id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/linear-attention#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"1487":{"id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention-3","page_id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/linear-attention#heading-2","content":"What It Optimizes"},"1488":{"id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention-4","page_id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/linear-attention#heading-3","content":"Practical Benefit"},"1489":{"id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention-5","page_id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/linear-attention#heading-4","content":"How It Works"},"1490":{"id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention-6","page_id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/linear-attention#heading-5","content":"Math Or Compute Schema"},"1491":{"id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention-7","page_id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/linear-attention#heading-6","content":"Compared To Nearby Modules"},"1492":{"id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention-8","page_id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/linear-attention#heading-7","content":"Example Architectures"},"1493":{"id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention-9","page_id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/linear-attention#heading-8","content":"Limitations And Tradeoffs"},"1494":{"id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention-10","page_id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/linear-attention#heading-9","content":"Why It Still Matters"},"1495":{"id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention-11","page_id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/linear-attention#heading-10","content":"Related"},"1496":{"id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention-12","page_id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/linear-attention#heading-11","content":"Tags"},"1497":{"id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention-13","page_id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/linear-attention#heading-12","content":"References"},"1498":{"id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention-14","page_id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention","tags":["attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/linear-attention#Linear Attention","content":"An attention variant that replaces explicit softmax dot-product attention with kernel or feature-map formulations that scale near-linearly with sequence length.\n\nLinear Attention\nAn attention variant that replaces explicit softmax dot-product attention with kernel or feature-map formulations that scale near-linearly with sequence length.\nStandard attention materializes an n-by-n score matrix before softmax, so cost grows quadratically with sequence length; linear attention applies a feature map to queries and keys so attention can be computed through associative updates or recurrence, trading exact softmax dot-product scoring for near-linear scaling on long sequences.\nWhat It Is\nLinear attention is an attention variant that reformulates attention without building the full softmax score matrix. Feature maps on queries and keys let the model accumulate key-value statistics in linear time rather than scoring every query-key pair explicitly.\nWhat It Optimizes\nLinear attention targets sequence-length scaling, attention compute cost, and memory bandwidth when dense quadratic attention would dominate runtime on long contexts.\nPractical Benefit\nTeams adopt linear attention when they need to process long sequences but cannot afford quadratic attention cost. Kernel or recurrence views let each new token update running statistics instead of revisiting the full score matrix.\nHow It Works\nQueries and keys pass through a feature map φ that makes their product associative. The model accumulates φ(K)ᵀV across positions and combines the result with φ(Q) at each step, avoiding explicit materialization of the full n-by-n attention matrix.\nMath Or Compute Schema\nWith feature map φ applied to queries and keys, linear attention computes output through associative products rather than softmax over all pairs. The formulas below contrast dense multi-head attention against linear attention that routes through φ and a normalization term.\nCompared To Nearby Modules\nCompared with multi-head attention, linear attention changes the compute mechanism rather than only sharing KV heads. Multi-query and grouped-query attention remain dense over allowed positions but reduce KV head count; linear attention pursues subquadratic sequence scaling through kernel or recurrence formulations.\nExample Architectures\nLinear attention appears in long-context models and research architectures that combine subquadratic attention layers with standard dense blocks to balance efficiency and expressiveness.\nLimitations And Tradeoffs\nFeature-map linear attention is not identical to softmax dot-product attention. Approximation quality depends on the chosen kernel, and some formulations sacrifice the exact pairwise scoring that dense attention provides.\nWhy It Still Matters\nAs context lengths grow, subquadratic attention options remain a practical design axis for models that must serve long sequences without quadratic attention cost on every layer.\nRelated\nTags\nReferences\nDense multi-head attention versus linear attention feature-map flow\nToggle MHA and linear attention to compare full softmax dot-product scoring against feature-map associative updates on one canvas\nHow linear attention compares with nearby attention variants"},"1499":{"id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention-15","page_id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention","tags":["attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/linear-attention","content":"linear attention"},"1500":{"id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention-16","page_id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention","tags":["attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/linear-attention","content":"subquadratic attention"},"1501":{"id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention-17","page_id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention","tags":["attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/linear-attention","content":"attention"},"1502":{"id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention-18","page_id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention","tags":["attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/linear-attention","content":"attention mechanism"},"1503":{"id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention-19","page_id":"/docs/modules/linear-attention","tags":["attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/linear-attention","content":"attention"},"1504":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention","type":"page","content":"Multi-Head Attention","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention"},"1505":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention-0","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention","tags":["attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention","content":"The baseline attention design that gives every query head its own key-value head pair."},"1506":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention-1","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention#heading-0","content":"Multi-Head Attention"},"1507":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention-2","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"1508":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention-3","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention#heading-2","content":"What It Optimizes"},"1509":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention-4","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention#heading-3","content":"Practical Benefit"},"1510":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention-5","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention#heading-4","content":"How It Works"},"1511":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention-6","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention#heading-5","content":"Math Or Compute Schema"},"1512":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention-7","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention#heading-6","content":"Compared To Nearby Modules"},"1513":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention-8","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention#heading-7","content":"Example Architectures"},"1514":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention-9","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention#heading-8","content":"Limitations And Tradeoffs"},"1515":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention-10","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention#heading-9","content":"Why It Still Matters"},"1516":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention-11","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention#heading-10","content":"Related"},"1517":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention-12","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention#heading-11","content":"Tags"},"1518":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention-13","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention"],"url":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention#heading-12","content":"References"},"1519":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention-14","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention","tags":["attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention#Multi-Head Attention","content":"The baseline attention design that gives every query head its own key-value head pair.\n\nMulti-Head Attention\nThe baseline attention design that gives every query head its own key-value head pair.\nTransformer blocks need each token position to gather context from others; multi-head attention (MHA) runs that lookup in parallel by splitting projected queries, keys, and values into H independent heads so each head can specialize while outputs are concatenated back together.\nWhat It Is\nMulti-head attention is the original scaled dot-product attention used in the Transformer. Each head computes its own attention distribution over keys and values, then the head outputs are merged before the next sublayer.\nWhat It Optimizes\nMHA targets representational breadth: distinct query heads can attend to different relationships in the same sequence without sharing key-value parameters.\nPractical Benefit\nModels keep full per-head expressiveness at training and inference time. MHA remains the reference design when quality matters more than KV-cache size, and it is the baseline against which multi-query attention and grouped-query attention are compared.\nHow It Works\nLinear projections produce H query heads, H key heads, and H value heads. Each query head i attends to its matching key head i and value head i, producing H outputs that are concatenated and projected again.\nMath Or Compute Schema\nThe formula below is the per-head attention computation used inside multi-head attention. Each head index i pairs its own query, key, and value tensors before outputs are merged.\nCompared To Nearby Modules\nCompared with multi-query attention, MHA stores one KV pair per query head, so cache size scales with H. Compared with grouped-query attention, MHA avoids shared KV groups and keeps the largest KV footprint in the head-sharing family.\nExample Architectures\nMHA appears in the original Transformer encoder-decoder, early GPT-style decoder-only language models, and many vision and speech transformers that adopt the standard attention block.\nLimitations And Tradeoffs\nAutoregressive inference must cache every key and value head, so memory and bandwidth grow with context length and head count. Serving long contexts often motivates MQA or GQA instead.\nWhy It Still Matters\nMHA is the conceptual baseline for every head-sharing variant: understanding its one-to-one query-to-KV mapping makes MQA and GQA tradeoffs easier to reason about.\nRelated\nTags\nReferences\nMulti-head attention versus multi-query attention head-count comparison\nToggle MHA and MQA to compare query-head count against KV-head count on one canvas\nHow MHA compares with nearby attention variants"},"1520":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention-15","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention","tags":["attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention","content":"MHA"},"1521":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention-16","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention","tags":["attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention","content":"multi-head attention"},"1522":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention-17","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention","tags":["attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention","content":"attention"},"1523":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention-18","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention","tags":["attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention","content":"attention mechanism"},"1524":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention-19","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention","tags":["attention"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/multi-head-attention","content":"attention"},"1525":{"id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","page_id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","type":"page","content":"Grouped-Query Attention","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"url":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention"},"1526":{"id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention-0","page_id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","content":"An attention variant that reduces KV cache memory by sharing key-value heads across query groups."},"1527":{"id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention-1","page_id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"url":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention#heading-0","content":"Grouped-Query Attention"},"1528":{"id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention-2","page_id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"url":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"1529":{"id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention-3","page_id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"url":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention#heading-2","content":"What It Optimizes"},"1530":{"id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention-4","page_id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"url":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention#heading-3","content":"Practical Benefit"},"1531":{"id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention-5","page_id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"url":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention#heading-4","content":"How It Works"},"1532":{"id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention-6","page_id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"url":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention#heading-5","content":"Math Or Compute Schema"},"1533":{"id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention-7","page_id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"url":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention#heading-6","content":"Compared To Nearby Modules"},"1534":{"id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention-8","page_id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"url":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention#heading-7","content":"Example Architectures"},"1535":{"id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention-9","page_id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"url":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention#heading-8","content":"Limitations And Tradeoffs"},"1536":{"id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention-10","page_id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"url":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention#heading-9","content":"Why It Still Matters"},"1537":{"id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention-11","page_id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"url":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention#heading-10","content":"Related"},"1538":{"id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention-12","page_id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"url":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention#heading-11","content":"Tags"},"1539":{"id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention-13","page_id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"url":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention#heading-12","content":"References"},"1540":{"id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention-14","page_id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention#Grouped-Query Attention","content":"An attention variant that reduces KV cache memory by sharing key-value heads across query groups.\n\nGrouped-Query Attention\nAn attention variant that reduces KV cache memory by sharing key-value heads across query groups.\nKV caches grow with context length and head count, raising memory use during long-context inference; grouped-query attention (GQA) lets several query heads share fewer key-value heads so the cache stores fewer KV tensors without collapsing to one shared head.\nWhat It Is\nGrouped-query attention is an attention variant derived from multi-head attention. It keeps multiple query heads but groups them so each group reads from the same key-value head pair.\nWhat It Optimizes\nGQA targets KV-cache footprint, memory bandwidth during autoregressive decoding, and the cost of serving long contexts when head count would otherwise multiply cache size.\nPractical Benefit\nTeams adopt GQA when they need multi-head expressiveness at training time but want leaner inference caches and less KV traffic at deployment time. GQA keeps more query diversity than multi-query attention while using a smaller cache than full multi-head attention.\nHow It Works\nQueries are partitioned into groups. Each group shares one key head and one value head. Attention scores are computed per query head against the shared KV pair for that group, then outputs are projected as usual.\nMath Or Compute Schema\nWith H query heads and G KV groups, each group size is H/G. The formulas below contrast how multi-head attention pairs every query head with its own KV heads versus grouped-query attention, which routes query heads through shared KV pairs per group.\nCompared To Nearby Modules\nCompared with multi-head attention, GQA reduces KV tensors. Compared with multi-query attention, GQA keeps more distinct query heads while still sharing KV heads within each group.\nExample Architectures\nGQA appears in large decoder-only language models that prioritize efficient long-context inference while retaining multi-head training dynamics.\nLimitations And Tradeoffs\nSharing KV heads can reduce representational flexibility versus full multi-head attention. The optimal group count depends on model scale and quality targets.\nWhy It Still Matters\nAs context windows grow, KV-cache efficiency remains a first-order serving constraint, so GQA stays a practical default between MHA fidelity and MQA compression.\nRelated\nTags\nReferences\nMulti-head attention versus grouped-query attention head-count comparison\nToggle MHA and GQA to compare query-head count against KV-head count on one canvas\nHow GQA compares with nearby attention variants"},"1541":{"id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention-15","page_id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","content":"GQA"},"1542":{"id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention-16","page_id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","content":"grouped-query attention"},"1543":{"id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention-17","page_id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","content":"grouped query attention"},"1544":{"id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention-18","page_id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","content":"attention"},"1545":{"id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention-19","page_id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","content":"attention mechanism"},"1546":{"id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention-20","page_id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","content":"kv-cache"},"1547":{"id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention-21","page_id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","content":"KV cache"},"1548":{"id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention-22","page_id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention","content":"key-value cache"},"1549":{"id":"/docs/modules/grouped-query-attention-23","page_id":"/