docs/modules/multi-query-attention#heading-4","content":"How It Works"},"1558":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention-6","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"url":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention#heading-5","content":"Math Or Compute Schema"},"1559":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention-7","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"url":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention#heading-6","content":"Compared To Nearby Modules"},"1560":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention-8","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"url":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention#heading-7","content":"Example Architectures"},"1561":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention-9","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"url":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention#heading-8","content":"Limitations And Tradeoffs"},"1562":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention-10","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"url":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention#heading-9","content":"Why It Still Matters"},"1563":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention-11","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"url":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention#heading-10","content":"Related"},"1564":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention-12","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"url":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention#heading-11","content":"Tags"},"1565":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention-13","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"url":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention#heading-12","content":"References"},"1566":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention-14","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention#Multi-Query Attention","content":"An attention variant that shares one key-value head across all query heads to minimize KV-cache memory.\n\nMulti-Query Attention\nAn attention variant that shares one key-value head across all query heads to minimize KV-cache memory.\nAutoregressive inference must store keys and values for every past token, and that KV cache grows with context length and head count; multi-query attention (MQA) keeps H query heads but projects them through a single shared key-value pair so the cache stores only one K tensor and one V tensor per layer.\nWhat It Is\nMulti-query attention is an attention variant derived from multi-head attention. Every query head still computes its own attention scores, but all heads read from the same key head and value head.\nWhat It Optimizes\nMQA targets KV-cache footprint and memory bandwidth during autoregressive decoding. Sharing one KV pair across all query heads minimizes the number of tensors stored per token.\nPractical Benefit\nServing stacks adopt MQA when long-context inference would otherwise multiply cache size by head count. MQA delivers the smallest KV footprint in the head-sharing family while keeping distinct query projections.\nHow It Works\nLinear projections still produce H query heads, but key and value projections collapse to a single head each. Every query head i attends against the shared K and V tensors, then outputs are concatenated and projected as usual.\nMath Or Compute Schema\nThe formulas below contrast how multi-head attention pairs every query head with its own KV heads versus multi-query attention, which routes all query heads through one shared KV pair.\nCompared To Nearby Modules\nCompared with multi-head attention, MQA stores one KV pair instead of H. Compared with grouped-query attention, MQA compresses further by sharing a single KV head across all query heads rather than G groups.\nExample Architectures\nMQA appears in decoder-only language models that prioritize inference throughput and lean KV caches, including some large-scale serving configurations that accept the representational tradeoff.\nLimitations And Tradeoffs\nSharing one KV head across all queries can reduce representational flexibility versus full multi-head attention or grouped-query attention. Quality-sensitive workloads may prefer GQA or MHA.\nWhy It Still Matters\nMQA established the head-sharing design space: it shows how far KV compression can go before grouped-query attention offers a middle ground between cache size and query diversity.\nRelated\nTags\nReferences\nMulti-head attention versus multi-query attention head-count comparison\nToggle MHA and MQA to compare query-head count against KV-head count on one canvas\nHow MQA compares with nearby attention variants"},"1567":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention-15","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention","content":"MQA"},"1568":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention-16","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention","content":"multi-query attention"},"1569":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention-17","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention","content":"attention"},"1570":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention-18","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention","content":"attention mechanism"},"1571":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention-19","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention","content":"kv-cache"},"1572":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention-20","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention","content":"KV cache"},"1573":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention-21","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention","content":"key-value cache"},"1574":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention-22","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention","content":"attention"},"1575":{"id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention-23","page_id":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention","tags":["attention","kv-cache"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/multi-query-attention","content":"kv-cache"},"1576":{"id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention","page_id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention","type":"page","content":"Sliding-Window Attention","tags":["attention","context-window"],"url":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention"},"1577":{"id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention-0","page_id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention","tags":["attention","context-window"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention","content":"An attention variant that restricts each query to a fixed local window of key positions instead of the full sequence."},"1578":{"id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention-1","page_id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","context-window"],"url":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention#heading-0","content":"Sliding-Window Attention"},"1579":{"id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention-2","page_id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","context-window"],"url":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention#heading-1","content":"What It Is"},"1580":{"id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention-3","page_id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","context-window"],"url":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention#heading-2","content":"What It Optimizes"},"1581":{"id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention-4","page_id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","context-window"],"url":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention#heading-3","content":"Practical Benefit"},"1582":{"id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention-5","page_id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","context-window"],"url":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention#heading-4","content":"How It Works"},"1583":{"id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention-6","page_id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","context-window"],"url":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention#heading-5","content":"Math Or Compute Schema"},"1584":{"id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention-7","page_id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","context-window"],"url":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention#heading-6","content":"Compared To Nearby Modules"},"1585":{"id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention-8","page_id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","context-window"],"url":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention#heading-7","content":"Example Architectures"},"1586":{"id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention-9","page_id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","context-window"],"url":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention#heading-8","content":"Limitations And Tradeoffs"},"1587":{"id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention-10","page_id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","context-window"],"url":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention#heading-9","content":"Why It Still Matters"},"1588":{"id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention-11","page_id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","context-window"],"url":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention#heading-10","content":"Related"},"1589":{"id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention-12","page_id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","context-window"],"url":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention#heading-11","content":"Tags"},"1590":{"id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention-13","page_id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention","type":"heading","tags":["attention","context-window"],"url":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention#heading-12","content":"References"},"1591":{"id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention-14","page_id":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention","tags":["attention","context-window"],"type":"text","url":"/docs/modules/sliding-window-attention#Sliding-Window Attention","content":"An attention variant that restricts each query to a fixed local window of key positions instead of the full sequence.\n\nSliding-Window Attention\nAn attention variant that restricts each query to a fixed local window of key positions instead of the full sequence.\nDense attention lets every query attend to every key across the sequence, so cost grows with the square of length; sliding-window attention applies a fixed local window so each position attends only to nearby keys, trading global reach for bounded compute and memory on long contexts.\nWhat It Is\nSliding-window attention is an attention variant that limits each query position to keys within a fixed neighborhood. Instead of a full n-by-n attention matrix, only entries inside the window receive non-zero weight.\nWhat It Optimizes\nSliding-window attention targets attention compute, memory bandwidth for score materialization, and the cost of serving long sequences when dense all-pairs attention would dominate runtime.\nPractical Benefit\nTeams adopt sliding-window attention when they need long-context modeling but cannot afford dense quadratic attention. Bounding the attended neighborhood reduces multiply-accumulate work and keeps attention maps within a predictable local footprint.\nHow It Works\nEach query position attends only to keys within W tokens to its left (and optionally right, depending on the pattern). Keys outside the window are zeroed before softmax normalization, so the model spends compute on local context rather than the full token grid.\nMath Or Compute Schema\nWith sequence length n and window size W, sliding-window attention applies a band mask before softmax. The formulas below contrast dense multi-head attention against window-limited attention that restricts which keys each query can reach.\nCompared To Nearby Modules\nCompared with multi-head attention, sliding-window attention limits reach to a local neighborhood rather than scoring all positions. Multi-query and grouped-query attention remain dense over allowed positions but reduce KV head count; sliding-window attention changes how far each query can look.\nExample Architectures\nSliding-window attention appears in long-context decoder models that combine local windows with periodic global layers or other patterns to recover distant dependencies.\nLimitations And Tradeoffs\nA fixed window cannot directly connect distant tokens in a single layer. Models that rely only on local windows may need stacked layers or companion patterns to move information across the full sequence.\nWhy It Still Matters\nAs sequence lengths grow, quadratic attention cost motivates locality patterns that preserve useful nearby signal while avoiding a full n-by-n score matrix on every layer.\nRelated\nTags\nReferences\nDense multi-head attention versus sliding-window local reach\nToggle MHA and sliding-window attention to compare full-sequence reach against fixed local windows on one canvas\nHow sliding-window attention compares with nearby attention variants"},"1592":{"id":"/docs/mod