iffusion architecture"],[891,"Diffusion Model"],[893,"Diffusion Model"],[902,"diffusion models"],[182,"discriminative classifier"],[168,"Discriminative Model"],[170,"Discriminative Model"],[180,"discriminative models"],[511,"Embedding"],[513,"Embedding"],[523,"embeddings"],[1140,"emergent abilities"],[1139,"Emergent behavior"],[1127,"Emergent Behavior"],[1129,"Emergent Behavior"],[409,"Empirical power-law relationships between model scale, compute, data, and downstream loss or capability—used to forecast training budgets and benchmark trends."],[419,"Empirical power-law relationships between model scale, compute, data, and downstream loss or capability—used to forecast training budgets and benchmark trends.\n\nScaling Law\nEmpirical power-law relationships between model scale, compute, data, and downstream loss or capability—used to forecast training budgets and benchmark trends.\nScaling laws describe predictable loss improvements when model size, dataset size, or compute increase along a training frontier, often as power laws until limits bend the curve.\nWhat It Is\nA scaling law is an empirical fit relating scale (parameters, training tokens, or compute) to a target such as validation loss or perplexity. Kaplan-style language-model laws showed smooth improvements over many orders of magnitude when training is near-optimal. The relationship is descriptive—not a guarantee that every architecture or objective follows the same exponents.\nWhy It Matters\nScaling laws help forecast whether a larger run is worth the budget and how much data a parameter count needs. They tie evaluation metrics to capacity: model capacity and parameter count set the frontier, generalization and perplexity track whether the run landed on it, and emergent behavior pages describe capabilities that may not appear on the same smooth curve.\nSimple Example\nIf doubling parameters cuts validation loss by a fixed fraction on a log-log plot across several sizes, you can extrapolate the next checkpoint’s expected perplexity before paying for the full training run—until the data-limited regime flattens the trend.\nWhere It Appears\nScaling papers, compute-optimal training recipes (Chinchilla-style tradeoffs), and roadmap slides comparing parameter counts. Architecture and model-capacity pages explain what is being scaled; perplexity and generalization pages show the measured outcomes.\nCommon Confusions\nA scaling law is not the same as emergent behavior—many metrics improve smoothly while specific capabilities appear abruptly. Laws fit historical runs; they do not remove the need for held-out evaluation or alignment checks on new tasks.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nAsk which axis was scaled (params, data, compute) and which metric was fit before trusting an extrapolation."],[381,"Encoder"],[383,"Encoder"],[393,"Encoder"],[394,"encoder block"],[1359,"encoder decoder"],[395,"encoder stack"],[1346,"Encoder-Decoder"],[1348,"Encoder-Decoder"],[1360,"encoder-decoder architecture"],[396,"encoding network"],[631,"Entropy"],[633,"Entropy"],[324,"environment model"],[1431,"Example Architectures"],[1471,"Example Architectures"],[1492,"Example Architectures"],[1513,"Example Architectures"],[1534,"Example Architectures"],[1560,"Example Architectures"],[1585,"Example Architectures"],[799,"expressive capacity"],[734,"Extra inputs—text prompts, class labels, images, or guidance weights—that steer a generative model without retraining the full parameter stack each time."],[744,"Extra inputs—text prompts, class labels, images, or guidance weights—that steer a generative model without retraining the full parameter stack each time.\n\nConditioning\nExtra inputs—text prompts, class labels, images, or guidance weights—that steer a generative model without retraining the full parameter stack each time.\nConditioning injects side information—prompts, class labels, or cross-attention context—so each generation step depends on both the current state and the control signal.\nWhat It Is\nConditioning signals are encoded—via text encoders, learned embeddings, or pooled features—and fused into the generative network at attention layers, FiLM layers, or as prepended tokens. Classifier-free guidance mixes conditional and unconditional forward passes in denoising models. Autoregressive models condition on prior tokens plus optional system or tool context in the prefix.\nWhy It Matters\nConditioning is the bridge between the two major generation paradigms: both autoregressive and denoising loops accept control inputs, but they attach them at different points in the stack. Understanding conditioning clarifies prompt engineering, adapter tuning, and why the same text encoder can steer image diffusion and multimodal chat.\nSimple Example\nA diffusion model receives a CLIP text embedding alongside each denoising step so \"a red bicycle\" shifts the score toward bicycle-shaped latents. A chat model prepends a system message token sequence so the autoregressive decoder sees policy instructions before the user turn.\nWhere It Appears\nText-to-image diffusion uses cross-attention conditioning; instruction-tuned language models use prefix conditioning; class-conditional GANs and diffusion use label embeddings. Autoregressive generation and denoising generation pages describe the loops that consume these signals.\nCommon Confusions\nConditioning is not fine-tuning: weights stay fixed while runtime inputs change behavior. It is also not the same as a hard constraint or decoder constraint algorithm—conditioning is learned soft steering. Prompt tokens in autoregressive models are conditioning, but not every context window entry is an independent control channel; some are simply prior generated tokens.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nAsk what extra signal is fused into each generation step and where in the network that fusion happens."],[487,"Extra memory an adaptive optimizer keeps beyond model weights, such as momentum and variance estimates for each parameter."],[497,"Extra memory an adaptive optimizer keeps beyond model weights, such as momentum and variance estimates for each parameter.\n\nOptimizer State\nExtra memory an adaptive optimizer keeps beyond model weights, such as momentum and variance estimates for each parameter.\nOptimizer state stores per-parameter running history used to shape each update—distinct from the weights themselves and required for faithful training resumes.\nWhat It Is\nModel parameters hold the learned weights, but adaptive optimizers also keep auxiliary tensors aligned with each parameter shape. Adam tracks exponential moving averages of gradients and squared gradients (often called m and v). Momentum methods keep velocity buffers. These tensors are optimizer state: they are updated every step and influence the effective learning rate per parameter.\nWhy It Matters\nSaving only model weights and reloading into a fresh optimizer resets training dynamics—you lose accumulated momentum and adaptive scaling. Large-language-model training checkpoints therefore include optimizer state, which can be several times the parameter memory footprint. Inference-only deployments usually discard optimizer state because weights alone are enough to run forward passes.\nSimple Example\nWith Adam, each weight w might have companion buffers m_w and v_w. On step t the optimizer reads gradient g_w, updates m_w and v_w with decay factors β₁ and β₂, then applies a scaled step to w. Those buffers—not the gradient from the current batch alone—determine how large the update is.\nWhere It Appears\nPyTorch `optimizer.state_dict()`, DeepSpeed ZeRO sharding, and Hugging Face Trainer checkpoints all persist optimizer buffers alongside weights. Distinctive chain phrase: Adam first and second moment buffers per parameter tensor.\nCommon Confusions\nOptimizer state is not the same as model parameters or gradients—parameters are what you learn, gradients are ephemeral signals from the current backward pass, and optimizer state is long-lived memory across steps. It also differs from activation checkpoints or KV cache used during inference. Mixing up optimizer state with EMA shadow weights (used in some eval setups) causes confusion when comparing checkpoint sizes.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nParameters are the weights; gradients say how to change them this step; optimizer state remembers past steps so updates stay stable and adaptive."],[929,"feature representation"],[1083,"Feed-forward network"],[1085,"Feed-forward network"],[1095,"feedforward network"],[1094,"FFN"],[200,"Formula And Symbols"],[973,"Formula And Symbols"],[670,"forward graph"],[681,"Foundation Model"],[683,"Foundation Model"],[693,"foundation models"],[16,"foundational concepts"],[36,"foundational concepts"],[56,"foundational concepts"],[76,"foundational concepts"],[107,"foundational concepts"],[135,"foundational concepts"],[158,"foundational concepts"],[189,"foundational concepts"],[210,"foundational concepts"],[234,"foundational concepts"],[254,"foundational concepts"],[279,"foundational concepts"],[301,"foundational concepts"],[350,"foundational concepts"],[371,"foundational concepts"],[398,"foundational concepts"],[425,"foundational concepts"],[481,"foundational concepts"],[506,"foundational concepts"],[531,"foundational concepts"],[556,"foundational concepts"],[576,"foundational concepts"],[599,"foundational concepts"],[621,"foundational concepts"],[651,"foundational concepts"],[676,"foundational concepts"],[702,"foundational concepts"],[728,"foundational concepts"],[750,"foundational concepts"],[780,"foundational concepts"],[802,"foundational concepts"],[833,"foundational concepts"],[854,"foundational concepts"],[881,"foundational concepts"],[937,"foundational concepts"],[962,"foundational concepts"],[983,"foundational concepts"],[1002,"foundational concepts"],[1027,"foundational concepts"],[1051,"foundational 