eans the model memorized spurious training patterns that fail on validation or live data, often visible when validation loss rises while training loss keeps falling.\nWhat It Is\nOverfitting is poor generalization caused by excessive fit to the training distribution: the model minimizes training loss by memorizing examples instead of learning stable features. High capacity, noisy labels, and too many training steps relative to data size are common drivers.\nWhy It Matters\nOverfitting is the mirror of generalization: product quality depends on held-out performance, not training curves alone. Linking overfitting to model capacity, loss design, and alignment data hygiene keeps architecture, training, and evaluation vocabulary consistent.\nSimple Example\nA classifier reaches 99% training accuracy but 60% on a validation set because it memorized background textures in training photos. Adding augmentation, early stopping, or weight decay widens the train–validation gap in the right direction.\nWhere It Appears\nFine-tuning small datasets on large language models, tabular models with leaky features, and diffusion models that reproduce training captions verbatim. Loss-function and optimizer-state concepts describe the training machinery that must be regularized to reduce overfitting.\nCommon Confusions\nOverfitting is not the same as underfitting or pure distribution shift: shift can hurt test performance even without memorization. Low training loss alone is not proof of overfitting—you need a comparison set. Memorizing public benchmarks is a form of overfitting to evaluation, not just training rows.\nRelated Concepts And Modules\nTags\nReferences\nReader Shortcut\nCompare training and validation curves—divergence with great training metrics is the overfitting smell test."],[7,"Where It Appears"],[26,"Where It Appears"],[46,"Where It Appears"],[66,"Where It Appears"],[92,"Where It Appears"],[118,"Where It Appears"],[147,"Where It Appears"],[174,"Where It Appears"],[220,"W